<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Aug. 11, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Buchanan Wins Reform Party Nod
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- In a victory bitterly contested by supporters of
party founder Ross Perot, Pat Buchanan won the Reform Party presidential
nomination tonight who refused to recognize the outcome. Their rival convention
named its own nominee. Buchanan and the nominee of the competing convention,
little-known physicist John Hagelin, may be headed to court to determine which
faction gains control of the party and $12.5 million in federal campaign
funding.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Venezuelan Leader Visits Indonesia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Fresh from a visit to Iraq, Venezuelan President
Hugo Chavez met Saturday with President Abdurrahman Wahid to discuss boosting
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries's global clout. Chavez is on a
whirlwind tour of OPEC nations to drum up support for a oil summit in Caracas
next month. He is also seeking backing for maintaining the price of oil. Chavez
arrived at the presidential palace in Jakarta on Saturday morning, but did not
speak to waiting reporters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't Adopts Simpler Health Forms
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an effort to reduce paperwork, the government has
adopted simpler health care forms for doctors to submit payment claims to
insurers by computer. The plan, announced Friday, establishes standard formats
for submitting electronic claims and other administrative health transactions.
All health care providers will be able to use the electronic format to bill for
their services, and all plans will be required to accept the forms. The
department expects the new forms to save the health care industry $29.9 billion
over 10 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Regulators Design New Tire Tests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Highway safety regulators are trying to update 30-year-old
tests for automobile tires that would prevent surprises like the problems that
led to the Firestone tire failures. Experts say existing tests are insufficient
and regulators were blindsided by the Firestone tire failures, culminating in a
recall of 6.5 million tires this week. Neither the tire maker,
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., nor Ford Motor Co., which used the tires on its
Explorer sport-utility vehicle, has been able to explain what caused the
failures.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Argentina Halts US Beef Exports
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Fresh and frozen Argentine beef exports to
the United States have been suspended temporarily over concerns of possible
foot-and-mouth disease contamination, officials said Friday. The self-imposed
suspension by Argentina, the world's fourth-largest beef exporter, was taken as
a preventive measure after cattle bred near the Paraguayan border were believed
to be infected with the disease. Argentine Agriculture Secretary Antonio
Berhongaray said the decision to halt exports of fresh, chilled, and frozen beef
would not affect Argentina's status as a country free of the disease, a
designation bestowed more than a year ago.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Aide: Colombia Advances
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia (AP) -- A key White House official said Friday that
President Clinton's upcoming visit to Colombia shows U.S. determination to be a
''reliable and dependable partner'' in the fight against drug trafficking. The
president's planned visit on Aug. 30 is the next logical American move following
passage last month of a $1.3 billion anti-narcotics measure to support
Colombia's war on drugs, said White House special envoy for the Americas,
Kenneth MacKay. MacKay, who is here in advance of Clinton's visit to this
Caribbean coast port city, said Colombia's fight against drugs will continue
regardless of who wins November's U.S. presidential elections.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Says Clinton's Embarrassing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore (AP) -- Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush
challenged Al Gore Friday to disavow conduct by President Clinton that
''embarrassed the nation.'' Bush questioned why his Democratic rival had not
been more outspoken in denouncing ethical transgressions by the departing
president.''If Al Gore has differences with the president, he ought to say them
loud and clear what they are,'' Bush said. The Texas governor said he wasn't
implying that Gore condoned such behavior.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 119; Nasdaq Gains 29
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Friday as blue chips surged on encouraging
economic data, but concerns for a second-half earnings slowdown kept technology
shares from broader gains. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 119.04 at
11,027.80, according to preliminary figures. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by
more than 2-to-1. The Nasdaq composite index was up 29.48 at 3,779.47.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Royals Defeat Orioles 7-6
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Rookie Mark Quinn kept up his second-half surge with
two homers and a double, driving in four runs as the Kansas City Royals beat the
Baltimore Orioles 7-6 Friday night. Quinn's 18 homers and 56 RBIs lead all
American League rookies. Since the All-Star break, he is batting .359
(42-for-117) with six homers and 18 RBIS.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
	    
</SUBHEAD>
