<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Alberto Gains Strength  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Alberto, the first hurricane of the Atlantic
season, was expected to swing northward and intensify slightly as
it churned over open seas Friday, but forecasters predicted it
would stay far from land.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto has been moving northwesterly, and forecasters said it
will pass well east of Bermuda. At 11 p.m. Friday, Alberto was
about 475 miles east northeast of Bermuda, moving north northeast
at 18 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane had sustained winds Friday night of 110 mph.
Forecasters expected Alberto would taper off and become a standard
storm system over cooler north Atlantic waters this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''The forecast is for slight strengthening in the short term and
weakening after 36 hours as colder water is encountered,'' Miles
Lawrence, a hurricane specialist at the National Hurricane Center
in Miami, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto had returned to hurricane strength Wednesday after
briefly weakening to a tropical storm.
</P>
<P>
   Another smaller system forecasters had been watching east of
Florida tapered off Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June 1 through November
30, peaking around Labor Day. Noted hurricane expert William Gray
is predicting 11 named storms, seven hurricanes and three major
hurricanes this year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
