<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Protection in War Zones Sought  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council, echoing concerns
raised last month by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, is calling for
better protection for children in war zones -- from girls who are
sexually exploited to boys who are recruited for combat.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassadors unanimously adopted a resolution calling for
governments to ratify key treaties protecting children and urging
governments and rebel groups to respect international laws that
safeguard the young.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution urges member states to protect and help refugees
and displaced persons, many of whom are children. It also asks
countries to provide children with ways to reintegrate once the
fighting ends.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations estimates that about 300,000 children have
been recruited, mostly by rebel groups, to fight wars from Sierra
Leone to Sri Lanka. Two million children were killed, 6 million
injured and 1 million orphaned by war between 1986 and 1996,
according to UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   Many who survive are orphaned or become heads of their
households, the resolution noted.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF hailed the resolution, saying the Security Council has
''reminded the world that it is both immoral and illegal to make
children the victims and protagonists of war.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution stems from Annan's report last month that
includes 55 proposals to protect children in war zones. The
proposals cover the recruitment of children into armies, the risk
of their being harmed by land mines and their suffering under
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Annan asked countries that support rebel factions -- with
military, political financial or other aid -- to require that rebels
comply with international norms as a condition of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Annan's recommendations were included in the
resolution, but the Security Council did agree to consider the
consequences sanctions have on children. The council has come under
fire for a decade of sanctions in Iraq, which have led to the
deaths of thousands of children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
