<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Democracy To Withstand Pinochet  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Far from threatening its democracy,
tensions over the legal troubles facing former dictator Gen.
Augusto Pinochet are a sign of Chile's growing political maturity,
its government says.
</P>
<P>
   Chileans should be proud of how the nation has been able to
advance in bringing the once all-powerful general to task for human
rights abuses during his regime, according to President Ricardo
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court last week stripped Pinochet of his legal
immunity by a 14-6 margin, opening the possibility of trying him in
Chile on human rights charges.
</P>
<P>
   The situation -- unthinkable only a few years back -- ''is a clear
demonstration that the country is transiting through a new era of
firm democracy,'' government spokesman Claudio Huepe said.
</P>
<P>
   Top military brass and rightists, who remain loyal to Pinochet,
paraded to Pinochet's heavily guarded suburban Santiago mansion
after the ruling to express their solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   The government called the military's support for its former
leader as ''an understandable gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Why do they wait until now, when he is old, ill and has lost
his power?'' Pinochet's wife, Lucia Hiriart, asked in a speech to
women supporting her husband.
</P>
<P>
   But fears the court's ruling would threaten the country's
democracy or provoke a violent military backlash have not been
realized. Acceptance of the ruling has been virtually unanimous,
although grudging at times.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet ''will do whatever the law mandates him to do,'' said
his lawyer, Pablo Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   His relatives and associates have said from the start that they
would accept the decision and continue their fight in the country's
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a politically motivated ruling, but in a democracy it
must be accepted,'' said right-wing congressman Alberto Cardemil.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Israel, a political scientist at the University of
Chile, said the country is belatedly dealing with a situation it
should have faced a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it is doing so with tremendous stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the military has accepted the trial and jailing of
other top-ranking officers on human rights charges in the past,
Israel said that ''if some incident happens, it will be an isolated
incident that would be quickly brought under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Popular reaction was also moderate. A few hundred supporters and
foes of the general held peaceful and brief demonstrations. Opinion
polls showed a majority of Chileans supported the removal of
Pinochet's immunity.
</P>
<P>
   The political consequences of the case, however, appear more
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Government efforts to rid Chile of the legal legacy from the
Pinochet era will likely come under attack as angry Pinochet
supporters harden their opposition in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The government needs the support of the right-wing opposition to
pass key bills, and in recent months the government and the
opposition had made progress in negotiations aimed at amending the
1980 constitution written by the Pinochet regime.
</P>
<P>
   The main changes sought by the government are the elimination of
nine Senate seats that are appointed instead of elected and the
restoration of full presidential authority over the military,
including power to fire its commanders.
</P>
<P>
   But talks appeared dead in the wake of the Pinochet ruling as
the opposition showed its power in Congress by denying quorum for
the first session scheduled after the court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opposition has gotten really angry, so I guess we will
have to wait until the anger fades,'' said Interior Minister Jose
Miguel Insulza.
</P>
<P>
   The imprisonment of Pinochet, who ruled Chile from 1973 to 1990,
is not imminent.
</P>
<P>
   If judge Juan Guzman, who will handle the case, actually opens a
trial, it should take years to conclude, and even his staunchest
foes admit they do not see him ever being sentenced, much less
jailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0112 </TRAILER>
