<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tire Recall Said Not To Harm Sales  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SUHR
<TEXT>
<P>
   The service garage in Jerry Reynolds' Dallas-area Prestige Ford
resembles a frenzied pit lane these days, from the constant whine
of lugnut drills to the feverish pace of crews in 56 bays replacing
recalled tires on Ford Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds doesn't find the crush too surprising -- or the fact
that shoppers in his showroom Friday still were interested in
buying new Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Bridgestone/Firestone Inc.'s recall of 6.5
million tires -- most of them on Ford SUVs and light trucks --
Explorer sales appear unaffected, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see it having any effect on SUV sales, period -- on any
make or any brand. People who want them want them,'' Reynolds said
from his dealership in Garland, Texas. ''It appears to the public
that it's an isolated Firestone problem, not a Ford one.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Center for Auto Safety, though, Clarence Ditlow isn't
convinced. He says the tire recall further highlights safety
concerns about SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   ''When one looks back three to four years from now, this may
well turn out to be a crucial factor in SUV sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 9,500 people are killed every year in rollover crashes,
according to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
More than 60 percent of fatalities in SUVs and more than 40 percent
of deaths in pickup trucks occur in rollovers, compared to 22
percent of car deaths.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ford said an electronic system meant to prevent
rollovers will soon be offered as an option in SUVs and pickup
trucks. The systems, which use sensors to keep a vehicle from
uncontrollably spinning, are widespread in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ford spokesman Terry Bresnihan wouldn't speculate about whether
the tire recall could affect the company's SUV sales. But he said
government studies have put the Explorer ''among the safest SUVs in
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer was one of the vehicles that whetted America's
appetite for SUVs. Ford sold 428,772 Explorers last year, 128,000
more than the nearest competitor, Jeep Grand Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. announced the voluntary recall
Wednesday involving radial ATX, radial ATX II and Wilderness AT
brand tires, which are standard equipment on some Ford SUVs and
light trucks. The government is investigating the tires in more
than 300 accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone spokesman Ken Fields noted that the
company recalled the tires voluntarily even before the
investigation was complete.
</P>
<P>
   ''We responded quickly to demonstrate that safety is our top
priority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Aikens, shopping at Detroit's Riverside Ford, said the
tire recall won't discourage SUV buyers. His advice: ''Just don't
buy a Ford with Firestone tires on it, or take the Firestones off
and get a different tire.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what shoppers are doing, at least at Reynolds'
Texas dealership, where he said consumers often are agreeing to buy
Explorers if the tires -- in many cases not among those being
recalled -- are replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hearing that all over the country,'' said Reynolds, who
also heads the Ford National Dealer Council. ''Customers are
saying, 'I feel good and safe with Explorers, but I won't buy one
with Firestone tires.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Reynolds' repair shop on Saturday will begin
indefinitely devoting its time to swapping tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has authorized nearly 3,000 dealers running out of
replacement tires to use tires from Firestone competitors Goodyear,
Michelin, General and Uniroyal, the Detroit Free Press reported in
Saturday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's move sidesteps Firestone's plan to spread the recall over
12 months, and apparently leaves the tire manufacturer responsible
for paying the warranty bills of Ford dealers who put its
competitors' products on Explorers and other light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone: http://www.bridgestone-firestone.com
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co.: http://www.ford.com
</P>
<P>
   National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
http://www.nhtsa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
