<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spies' Convictions Upheld in Court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A federal appeals court on Friday upheld
the espionage convictions of two spies for the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously upheld the October 1998 convictions of former Pentagon
lawyer Theresa Maria Squillacote and her husband, Kurt Alan Stand,
a former labor union representative. She was sentenced to 21 years
and 10 months in prison; he was sentenced to 17 years and six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had described the Washington, D.C., couple as
dedicated communists who hated the United States and were willing
to spy for any country.
</P>
<P>
   They said the couple helped set up a spy ring for the former
East Germany and passed classified documents to an FBI agent they
thought was a South African intelligence officer. The two were
caught in 1997 after the FBI learned of their attempts to contact
the Communist Party in South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
