<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Calls Clinton Embarrassing  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. (AP) -- Raising his right hand, George W. Bush
promises to add a personal vow to his presidential oath of office,
a vow to restore honor and integrity to the White House. That
pledge has an edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential nominee sharpened it by raising the
White House sex scandal as a campaign topic, saying President
Clinton had ''embarrassed the nation'' in the Monica Lewinsky
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that since Vice President Al Gore, his Democratic
opponent, is promising a fresh start, he should tell the voters
where he differs with Clinton on policy and ''everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If he's got a problem with what went on in the past, he ought
to explain what it is,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   With those comments aboard his campaign jet Friday, Bush
directly, but still cautiously, raised the scandal as a talking
point in his campaign against Gore. Bush said he did not intend to
make an issue of the Clinton scandal, although by discussing it he
effectively did so. He also said he was not suggesting that Gore
condoned the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the election is about the future, not about the past.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, campaigning with Bush, said the
same. He said the important issue is ''vision for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The other stuff is of secondary importance to the American
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even as a secondary concern, weariness and lingering
resentment of Clinton would be an asset for Bush against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president sharply rebuked Clinton for the affair in a
television interview 14 months ago. ''What he did was
inexcusable,'' Gore said on ABC. He said the president had lied to
him about it, as he lied to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton revived the subject himself with a public confessional
to a convention of clergymen in suburban Chicago on Thursday. He
spoke of his efforts to rebuild his personal life after his
''terrible mistake'' in the affair that led to his impeachment in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that Clinton had said much the same thing before. By
saying them as he headed for the Democratic National Convention in
Los Angeles, Clinton stirred the subject when the Gore campaign
would prefer to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Bush an opening to remind people of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   It has been there by indirection in the final lines of his
campaign speeches since he became a candidate. Closing a rally at
the University of Portland on Friday, Bush gave the familiar
gesture, the upraised right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I put my hand on the Bible on that day in January 2001, I
will swear to uphold the laws of the land,'' he said. ''But I will
also swear to uphold the honor and the integrity of the office to
which I have been elected, so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said Bush will become the first
Republican to carry the state since Ronald Reagan because
''Oregonians are tired of the ring in the bathtub'' and want honor
and dignity restored.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in California, McCain joined the man who defeated
him for the GOP nomination for a three-day campaign swing up the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   They were flying on Saturday to Arizona, where Bush and his
wife, Laura, will be overnight guests of the senator and Mrs.
McCain at their ranch in Sedona. McCain said he will barbecue them
a dinner of chicken and ribs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0129 </TRAILER>
