<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Makes Environmental Stop  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Al Gore is making a highly personal trip to
his environmental roots, hoping to ease concern among critics that
he has lost his fervor for protecting the air and water.
</P>
<P>
   Aides insist that Gore's commitment has remained consistent, and
he'll renew that vow with a tour of the homestead of author Rachel
Carson, whose 1962 classic ''Silent Spring'' launched what has
become the modern environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, awaiting the Democratic presidential
nomination, was talking up his environmental record Saturday, even
as he called for more.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm proud that even though we have far more to do, we now have
the cleanest air and water in a generation,'' Gore said in remarks
prepared for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''Throughout his career, Al Gore has been taking on polluters to
clean up our air and water,'' said spokesman Doug Hattaway.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was headed to Springdale and a tour of Carson's modest
homestead, hoping to send an environmental signal. He planned to
announce no new policy proposals, but his appearance acknowledges a
thorny political problem he faces from the left.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was making his environmental case in the strongest terms,
calling for ''a future where the smog of cities doesn't choke our
kids and block the afternoon sun.''
</P>
<P>
   He was stumping without his running mate, Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, for the first time since his selection. Lieberman
went home to observe the Jewish Sabbath, and won't be campaigning
from sunset on Fridays until sunset on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he arrived at the event, Gore was turning his
attention to the environment, focusing on global warming at a
fund-raiser in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''With some, it's still controversial,'' said Gore. ''I really
don't know why because Mother Nature is insistent making the point
that we're really going to have to wake up and do something about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore argued the nation should seize the opportunity, and begin
developing cleaner technology to market in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going to less-polluting technologies can position our
industries to lead the world in this century as we did in the
last,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The environment was one of the first issues Gore took on when he
entered Congress, and his book ''Earth in the Balance'' is an
argument for environmental activism.
</P>
<P>
   Republican critics cite passages from that book to suggest that
Gore's an environmental radical who wants to do such things as
eliminate the internal combustion engine and increase gasoline
prices. Gore rejects those assertions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore has come under fire from the left,
particularly from Green Party candidate Ralph Nader. Those critics
say that Gore has been stung by criticism of his book, and has
backed away from environmental activism.
</P>
<P>
   By paying homage to environmental pioneer Carson, Gore hopes to
answer that criticism by linking himself to the author of the book
that first raised questions about the wide use of chemicals in food
production and the impact of those chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Carson taught zoology at the University of Maryland in the
1930s, and had long service with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. Though she's best known by ''Silent Spring,'' she also
wrote ''The Sea Around Us'' which examines water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway argued that Gore can draw sharp distinctions with rival
George W. Bush on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaigned his way toward next week's Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles as officials disclosed his daughter,
Karenna Gore Schiff, would deliver one of three nominating speeches
for the vice president on Wednesday night. The other two will be by
Lois DeBerry, a friend of the vice president and a member of the
Tennessee Legislature, and actor Tommy Lee Jones, a Harvard
classmate of Gore's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USC Buys Downtown Hotel  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA WERNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Some of the prime accommodations at the
Democratic National Convention are being offered by the University
of Southern California, south-central LA's newest real estate
mogul.
</P>
<P>
   The private, richly endowed university paid $26 million for a
240-room high-rise Radisson Hotel across from its campus this
month, the latest example of universities in blighted urban areas
moving beyond their borders with social outreach and real estate
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   USC, which has 28,000 students and an endowment of $1.5 billion,
occupies a 150-acre campus surrounded by neighborhoods that in
recent decades have been among Los Angeles' most notorious. The
campus afforded a front-row view of the 1992 riots. But while other
downtown institutions have fled west, the university has refused to
budge from its 120-year-old home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're an urban university,'' said Bing Cherrie, USC's
associate vice president for planning. ''We've had several real
estate developers in our history try to woo us out, and our
trustees have always said no.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for wealthy universities to own hotels near
campus. In the past decade Harvard developed a posh hotel in
Harvard Square and Yale purchased a bed and breakfast that was in
danger of decline.
</P>
<P>
   Like the University of Pennsylvania, which transformed a West
Philadelphia parking lot into an upscale shopping center, or
Trinity College in Hartford, Conn., which spent hundreds of
thousands of dollars to buy and tear down crack houses, USC has
begun to take an active role in its environment.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hope next week's Democratic convention will both
showcase and promote that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people don't quite understand and think a university
is strictly academics doing research. But in many cases when you
have a university in an inner-city area they wear many hats,'' said
Jack Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp. ''They're there forever, so they're protecting
their interests and probably taking a longer-range look.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's purchase of the hotel follows a similar one a year ago of
a nearby shopping center that includes a movie theater and a drug
store. The university paid $25 million for the complex.
</P>
<P>
   The university, meanwhile, has poured resources into five local
public schools and sent campus police on patrol in the
south-central community that borders the campus. Crime has fallen
and property values are up.
</P>
<P>
   USC's real estate acquisitions were long viewed suspiciously by
residents fearful that the university was interested only in its
own property values and not in the low-income, working-class
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism fit in with USC's reputation as an academically
lightweight school for rich, white kids -- the University of Spoiled
Children.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a history of redevelopment in this neighborhood, and
USC's been the principal beneficiary,'' said Sandra McNeill of the
Figueroa Corridor Coalition for Economic Justice, a coalition
representing more than a dozen area groups that monitors USC's
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The shabby apartment buildings that line the streets around USC,
with bars on the windows and paint peeling from the walls, seem to
belong to a different world than the well-manicured campus.
Residents said USC is generally a good neighbor. But the contrast
makes some uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   Catalina Mendoza, 27, said she has lived in different apartments
near campus for six years with her sister Francisca and her two
young children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think if it's for the students it's a good thing,'' Mendoza
said of the Radisson purchase. ''But if it's to get the university
more money, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Another local resident, Lucille Lee, was waiting for the bus on
a recent afternoon seated on a stoop across from campus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel it's good to expand. It's good for the community,
education-wise,'' said Lee, 60. But, ''I still feel that they
should communicate more with the community and let the community
know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   USC officials said the university's investment in the
neighborhood benefits everyone involved. An urban university's
growth inevitably courts criticism from neighbors, they said,
whether they're the well-heeled Greenwich Village denizens around
New York University or the poorer residents of Harlem near
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may be in our own self-interest to do so, but we do have
this urban, city commitment,'' Cherrie said. ''I don't know that
we'll ever be able to satisfy everyone who thinks we're
encroaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0131 </TRAILER>
