<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Media Agree To End Barbs  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The news media of South and North
Korea have agreed to end their decades-old mudslinging at each
other as a thaw spreads across the divided Korean peninsula after a
half-century of animosity.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was adopted Friday in the North Korean capital of
Pyongyang, where 46 South Korean newspaper and broadcast presidents
met their North Korean counterparts in a rare weeklong visit to the
communist state, which had been virtually closed to outside media.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, news media were at the forefront of the ideological
confrontation by trading barbs at the communist government in the
North and the pro-Western government in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ''The media organizations of the North and the South will avoid
confrontation between compatriots and stop slanders and calumnies,
which hurt national reconciliation and unity, in keeping with the
prevailing situation,'' the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by the South Korean news executives came after leaders
of the two Koreas agreed to promote reconciliation during their
summit in June. Relations have improved rapidly since.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations of both Koreas will strive to help implement
the summit agreement, said the news media agreement, carried late
Friday by the North's official foreign news outlet, KCNA.
</P>
<P>
   They will ''cooperate with each other in news service and other
press activities and deepened mutual understanding and trust
through contacts, visits and exchange,'' it said. North Korea
agreed to dispatch a delegation of news media executives to visit
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean executives are expected to return home late
Saturday on board a chartered plane flying the first direct air
route between Seoul and Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The air route was opened to carry 100 people from each Korea who
will cross their heavily armed border on Tuesday for four-day
temporary family reunions with relatives separated by the 1950-53
Korean War. The war ended without a peace treaty in 1953 and the
border has been sealed ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Reuniting separated families was a key part of the summit
agreements between North Korean leader Kim Jong Il and South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   The 46 South Korean newspaper and broadcast presidents began
their trip to North Korea last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Southern media used to describe Kim Jong Il as an unpredictable
recluse sponsoring terrorism, while North Korea had called the
South's media the ''stooges of reactionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they have recently toned down their hostile rhetoric,
uneasiness lingers. The head of the conservative Chosun Daily, a
vocal critic of the communist regime, refused to join the
delegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
