<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturdday, Aug. 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NTSB Releases EgyptAir Reports
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The terrifying last moments of EgyptAir Flight 990 show
the captain battling in vain to save his plane and the 217 people aboard -- a
struggle that probably will add to the debate over what caused the crash.
Co-pilot Gameel El-Batouty was at the controls when the Boeing 767 nosed into
its fatal dive into the Atlantic Ocean. Some investigators have speculated he
crashed the plane deliberately. Egyptian authorities have denied that
suggestion. The National Transportation Safety Board released 1,665 pages of
fact-finding reports into the crash, routine in such major investigations. The
reports set forth what has been learned so far, but do not provide analysis or
suggest a probable cause.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Buchanan Wins Reform Party Nod
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- In a victory bitterly contested by supporters of
party founder Ross Perot, Pat Buchanan won the Reform Party presidential
nomination tonight who refused to recognize the outcome. Their rival convention
named its own nominee. Buchanan and the nominee of the competing convention,
little-known physicist John Hagelin, may be headed to court to determine which
faction gains control of the party and $12.5 million in federal campaign
funding.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Courts Women's Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Amid stockroom shelves piled with handsewn dolls, Al
Gore and Joseph Lieberman pitched their tax-cut plan -- in dollars-and-cents,
us-versus-them terms -- to women voters whose sagging support in polls worries
the Democratic presidential ticket. On a Friday devoted to women and union
workers, Vice President Gore threaded his message with references to the
performance record he shares with President Clinton. But he also found himself
again juggling the hot potato of Clinton's personal conduct in the White House.
Women voters gave a decisive boost to Clinton's 1996 re-election but polls show
they aren't giving Gore much of a lift.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Montana U. Makes Fire Exceptions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOULDER, Mont. (AP) -- With too many fires and not enough firefighters, the
Montana university system told students Friday they can report for fall classes
three weeks late if they stay on the fire lines. The dangers became all too real
Friday to firefighters in Wyoming, where a wind-fuel wildfire engulfed a truck,
killing one firefighter and burning another on the Wind River Indian
Reservation.It was the sixth firefighter death involving U.S. wildfires this
year. Strong winds had pushed flames out of control, forcing firefighters to
back off a 25,000-acre fire and a 5,000-acre fire, both burning in the sparsely
populated area of central Wyoming.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Regulators Design New Tire Tests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Highway safety regulators are trying to update 30-year-old
tests for automobile tires that would prevent surprises like the problems that
led to the Firestone tire failures. Experts say existing tests are insufficient
and regulators were blindsided by the Firestone tire failures, culminating in a
recall of 6.5 million tires this week. Neither the tire maker,
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., nor Ford Motor Co., which used the tires on its
Explorer sport-utility vehicle, has been able to explain what caused the
failures.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
ABC Reporter Apologizes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Reporter John Stossel apologized Friday night on ABC's
''20/20'' for using inaccurate information in two earlier reports on the safety
of organic food. Stossel prefaced the apology by defending other aspects of the
reports and said the mistakes were inadvertent. The apology was ordered by ABC
News, which also reprimanded Stossel and suspended a producer. Critics wanted
Stossel fired. In the reports, aired in February and again July 7, Stossel said
organic food was no safer than regular food and warned it could even be
dangerous. Stossel reported that an examination of produce conducted for ABC
News found that there was no pesticide residue on either conventional samples or
organic ones.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 119; Nasdaq Gains 29
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Friday as blue chips surged on encouraging
economic data, but concerns for a second-half earnings slowdown kept technology
shares from broader gains. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 119.04 at
11,027.80, according to preliminary figures. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by
more than 2-to-1. The Nasdaq composite index was up 29.48 at 3,779.47.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Angels Beat Yankees 8-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Garret Anderson and Mo Vaughn drove in three runs
apiece as the Anaheim Angels beat the New York Yankees 8-3 Friday night. Scott
Schoeneweis (6-6) won for only the second time in 13 starts, allowing three runs
-- two earned -- and nine hits in 6 2-3 innings with a career-high nine
strikeouts. Orlando Hernandez (8-9) had his second unimpressive outing since
coming off the disabled list last Sunday, losing for the ninth time in 13
decisions. Hernandez allowed seven runs and nine hits in 6 1-3 innings.
</P>
