<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sorenstam Leads du Maurier Classic  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   AYLMER, Quebec (AP) -- One thing is clear after two rounds of the
du Maurier Classic: The Royal Ottawa Golf Club is Lorie Kane's home
course.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sweden's Annika Sorenstam held a 1-stroke lead at 6-under
138 midway through the last major of the year in women's golf, she
and everyone else have to contend with Canada's favorite golfer and
the fans who are turning out to cheer on Kane.
</P>
<P>
   Those supporters streamed after Kane on Friday as she shot the
best round of the day, 5-under 67, and moved alone into second
place.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans held up a ''PEI'' banner in honor of Kane's native
Prince Edward Island. Some kids had on T-shirts reading
''I-am-Kane-adian.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, people wearing red or white -- Canada's colors -- were
scrambling to gain a vantage point around the Royal Ottawa course
to watch Kane.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never experienced this before, ever,'' Kane said. ''This
is what we work for. This is what we are, we're in the
entertainment business and we try to bring people out to introduce
them to the game of golf and the LPGA. And it's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane won last week in St. Louis for the first time in her
five-year LPGA career after a string of nine second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been waiting my whole life to win a golf tournament ...
the weight of the world is gone,'' she said Friday. ''And I'm out
here just having a blast. And I am as relaxed as I appear. I'm glad
I look relaxed, because I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kane is carrying another burden at the du Maurier. With the
tobacco company's sponsorship of Canada's only LPGA event being
terminated after this year due to government restrictions on
cigarette advertising, Kane said she wants to put on a good show to
entice another sponsor to keep the tournament alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I truly believe that someone will see what's going on with
this tournament and how important it is to Canadian sport, not just
golf, but sport and women's sport for sure, that we're going to
find somebody to pick this up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, who will be paired with Kane on Saturday, played one
group ahead of Kane both Thursday and Friday and said she could
tell from the roar of the crowd when Kane hit a shot and when her
playing partners -- Laura Davies and Pat Hurst -- did.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's her crowd. But the crowds here, they've very golf
knowledgeable,'' said Sorenstam, who is seeking her tour-leading
sixth victory of the year and a third career major. ''They don't
clap on your backswing, and I think that's the key here. They might
cheer louder for her, which is natural, but they're very
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam talked on Wednesday and Thursday about the need to
control her nerves. As the leader on Friday, Sorenstam said she now
has to turn the pressure of being ahead to her advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nerves is part of the game,'' she said. ''That's the thrill
about it. I love the challenge, and you come down the stretch and
have a lot of adrenaline and feeling the pressure. That's what I
strive for. I don't like the pressure; but on the other hand, I
love the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana D'Alessio said she has had enough of that pressure for
now. The tour rookie from New Jersey led Sorenstam and four others
by two strokes after Thursday's first round, but she struggled
Friday to a 1-over 73 and was tied with Juli Inkster and Laura
Philo for third at 4-under 140.
</P>
<P>
   With her first lead ever in an LPGA tournament -- not to mention
a major tournament -- D'Alessio said she slept badly Thursday night,
couldn't eat Thursday night or Friday before her round and in
general struggled mightily with her nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just a tough day,'' D'Alessio said. ''I'm really,
really tired and really emotionally drained. But I have two more
days to go. So I'm going to find some more adrenalin.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster had a 4-under 68 Friday, taking her accustomed spot on
the leader board at a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb, chasing a $1 million bonus from Nabisco if she can
win her third major tournament of the year at the du Maurier, shot
an even-par 72 Friday and was at 1-under 143, five strokes off the
pace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
