<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Wins 100 at Weltklasse  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA BULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Maurice Greene is back. And Marion
Jones never went away.
</P>
<P>
   Marking a jubilant return from injury, Greene reasserted his
control in the 100 meters at the Weltklasse Golden League track
meet Friday with the third-fastest time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones recovered from a slow start to win the women's 100 --
continuing an unbeaten streak in the sprint dating back nearly
three years. She also fought off tough competition to capture the
women's long jump, boosting her hopes of achieving her dream of
five gold medals in next month's Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring himself only ''about 85 percent'' fit after a strained
hamstring that forced him out of the 200 at the U.S. trials last
month, Greene crossed in 9.94 seconds ahead of a star-studded field
with eight of the top-10 sprinters this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm back,'' he announced after the race, his eyes shining and
a huge grin lighting up his face.
</P>
<P>
   ''As you see, I am OK and healthy,'' said Greene, who ran his
30th race under 10 seconds . ''I felt a little sluggish after being
off with injury, but it's getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Obadele Thompson of Barbados was second in 9.97, while
Trinidad's Ato Boldon was third in 10.00 flat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite posting the season's fastest 100 time of 9.91 in Japan
back in May and the second fastest in 9.93 at the U.S. trials in
Sacramento, Greene has had an up-and-down 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   His injury in the 200 against Michael Johnson in the U.S. trials
eliminated him from that race in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   But he played down the disappointment of having to drop the 200
from his Olympic ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have two gold medals to go and get,'' he said, referring to
the 100 and relay. ''And after that there will be more World
Championship medals, and more Olympic medals,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   While Greene professed to be unhappy with his relatively slow
finish, Jones complained about her bad start in the sprint after
being pulled up for a false start.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a horrible day, technically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones -- who posted the fastest 100 time of the season in 10.78
in London last weekend, crossed first in 10.95 -- edging runner-up
Inger Miller by .01.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about when she last lost a sprint race, Jones said, ''In
Japan in 1997,'' referring to a loss to Merlene Ottey in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Ottey raced in her first big international event since being
cleared of doping charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''Merlene brings a certain something to the race,'' Jones said.
''I was excited to see her back because it's like running against a
legend, something I can tell my grandkids about someday.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Jamaican, who has a record seven Olympic medals,
basked in the crowd applause after finishing third in 11.06.
</P>
<P>
   ''I put a lot of pressure on myself,'' said Ottey, who tested
positive for nandrolone in Lausanne last year and subsequently
pulled out of the world championships in Seville. ''The time is
good and I feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones prevailed in the long jump with her first victory of the
season, leaping 22 feet, 9 inches, just ahead of Bulgaria's Iva
Prandzheva.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very satisfied because the field is probably the same one
that will be in Sydney,'' Jones said. ''It wasn't a very long jump,
but it was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Morocco's Hicham Guerrouj, who had hoped to set a new world
record in the 1,500, crossed in 3 minutes, 27.21, comfortably
beating 21-year-old Noah Ngeny of Kenya, who had the previous best
time this year of 3:29.99. It was the third-fastest time ever.
</P>
<P>
   ''I showed my rivals and my admirers that I'm the best,'' El
Guerrouj said. ''It's an Olympic year and it's very special for me.
I hope to continue like this for the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Former world champion Maria Mutola of Mozambique won the women's
800 meters for the eighth consecutive year, crossing in 1:56.90,
the third-best time of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela Szabo of Romania also declared her Olympic intentions,
posting the fastest time of the season in the 3,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
