<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beford Claims Olympic Spot  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- B.J. Bedford is certainly persistent. She's
also an Olympian -- finally. Bedford made the U.S. swim team on her
fourth trip to the trials, with a little last-minute help from a
stranger on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford ended her 12-year wait with a victory in the 100-meter
backstroke Friday on the third night of the trials. She won in 1
minute, 1.85 seconds, ahead of Courtney Shealy of Columbia, S.C.,
who hung on for the second Olympic berth in 1:02.05.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final 10 meters, Bedford had one thought on her mind.
''Good God, where is the wall?'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Krayzelburg was thinking the same thing in the men's 100
back. Considered most likely to lower his own world record at the
trials, he went out too fast and faded at the end to win in 53.84
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I dove for the wall and made my dolphin kick, the wall
wasn't there yet, so I had to take one more kick,'' he said. ''It's
a learning experience for Sydney. For the next five weeks, I have
to work on swimming my own race. At this meet, you get caught up in
the emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedford certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   Unnerved as the day wore on, Bedford tried to call a sports
psychologist she regularly consults at the U.S. Olympic Training
Center in Colorado Springs, Colo. But the woman wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ''So I talked to some other guy,'' she said. ''He made me feel a
little better. I need to call him back and thank him.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bedford just missed the team by finishing third
in the 100 back at the trials. She was bartending in Texas during
the Atlanta Games, pouring drinks while customers watched swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was like, 'Get that crap off the TV,''' she said earlier in
the week, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Lea Mauer, the American record-holder in the 100 back, finished
third, missing a spot on the team by two-tenths of a second. The
high school English teacher in Lake Forest, Ill., hung over the
lane marker, covering her face in anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's more sad people than happy people at this meet,'' she
said. ''I swam a good race plan, and it just wasn't good enough.
For some reason, it was harder than it should've been.''
</P>
<P>
   With a sellout crowd of 4,500 at the Indiana University
Natatorium cheering him on, Krayzelburg and Neil Walker competed in
what was essentially a two-man race.
</P>
<P>
   Walker earned a spot on the Olympic team at 54.85 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Davis broke a 12-year-old American record in the 200 free,
winning in 1:47.26. That eclipsed Matt Biondi's mark of 1:47.72 in
the 1988 Seoul Olympics, but was still nearly two seconds off the
world record, held by Australian Ian Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 27, of Austin, Texas, won three gold medals in the 1996
Atlanta Games -- the most of any male athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Goldblatt of Austin finished second in 1:48.12 to make his
first Olympic team at 1:48.12. Chad Carvin and Klete Keller, who
already qualified for the team, finished 3-4 to earn spots on the
800 relay in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Megan Quann of Puyallup, Wash., also is heading
to the Olympics for the first time after winning the 100
breaststroke in 1:07.26 -- just 0.14 off her American record set a
day earlier. Staciana Stitts of Carlsbad, Calif., took the other
spot at 1:07.79.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.usa-swimming.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0239 </TRAILER>
