<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Driving Stolen Cars in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By OSWALD ALONSO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUERNAVACA, Mexico (AP) -- It could go down as one of the
greatest used car deals in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers grew suspicious and called for an inquiry into the
loaning of 75 stolen cars after a Roman Catholic bishop was seen
driving one of them in March. They demanded authorities explain.
</P>
<P>
   A state attorney general's office report released Friday says
that police commanders, journalists, the bishop and a social
activist have been driving stolen cars recovered by authorities in
the central Mexican state of Morelos.
</P>
<P>
   The 75 stolen vehicles loaned by police included Jeep Cherokees
and Volkswagen Jettas, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A clearly irritated Bishop Luis Reynoso Cervantes of the
Cuernavaca Diocese said the matter was being blown out of
proportion. He said police wanted to place the cars on exhibit so
the community could see what they had recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to tell you that a lot of times they exhibit the cars
so that the victims can identify them,'' said Reynoso Cervantes,
adding that the truck was given to a priest and was being used only
until the church got the funds to buy its own. The truck has since
been returned to the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The news caused an uproar Friday among opposition state
lawmakers who demanded 25 cars still on the road be returned to the
state's attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ''This should be punished for the illegal use of these stolen
cars,'' said Rep. Juan Ignacio Suarez Huape of the center-left
Democratic Revolution Party. ''There is no legal authority that
allows authorities to hand over seized goods for what they call
'use and exhibition.'''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker also said former state Attorney General Jose
Leonardo Castillo Pombo should be held responsible. Castillo Pombo,
who resigned last year amid accusations of having links to drug
traffickers, authorized the cars to be loaned, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report obtained by The Associated Press lists four former
top police officials among those found driving the cars, including
two commanders who were dismissed on accusations of extortion and
alleged ties to kidnapping rings. One commander was later rehired.
</P>
<P>
   The report also names a leader of a state peasant organization
and eight journalists, including radio, TV and newspaper reporters.
</P>
<P>
   State Prosecutor Rogelio Sanchez Gatica condemned the practice
and ordered the cars to be returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0249 </TRAILER>
