<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Author Smiley Learned From Horses  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Pulitzer-winning author Jane
Smiley says her new interest in horses has taught her many things,
including simply to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't realize until I had a horse how much time I spent
preoccupied. I had to ask for help and take lessons,'' said Smiley,
who spoke Monday at the National Racing Hall of Fame induction
ceremony here.
</P>
<P>
   She won a 1992 Pulitzer Prize for her novel ''A Thousand Acres''
about a farming family; her latest book is set at a racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley said the Pulitzer did not change her life, but that
horses did.
</P>
<P>
   ''He taught me to pay attention,'' she told the audience about
her first horse, which has been joined by 18 more. ''He gave me the
feeling of grace, power, the feeling of forward movement and
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He also taught me to relax,'' Smiley said. ''I found out
quickly that a horse won't relax when you ride him unless you
relax, too. ... I knew that everyday I would learn something about
the horses and about myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 0317 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
