<DOCNO> APW20000812.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton ducks debate invitations from Democratic challenger  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Contrary to what many New Yorkers believe,
Hillary Rodham Clinton is not yet the official U.S. Senate nominee
of the Democratic Party. She faces a Sept. 12 primary against an
orthopedic surgeon from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dr. Mark McMahon hasn't been able to get the time of day
from the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Pending federal court action, she could also face several other
Democrats in the primary. None, including McMahon, are household
names and none seem likely to threaten her chances of going up
against Republican U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio in November.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, McMahon managed to collect the signatures of more
than 40,000 Democrats statewide to win a spot on the primary
ballot. He needed at least 15,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, McMahon has been unsuccessfully trying to get the
first lady to meet him in a series of debates on such things as
health care, education, the economy and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that out of respect for the 4.9 million Democrats in
the state she should debate the home-grown candidate on the issues
New Yorkers care most about,'' the physician said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon has been making much of the fact that Clinton lacks New
York roots. She only moved to the state in January.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon is not alone in his inability to get an answer from
Clinton on whether she will debate him. Consider this exchange
between reporters and the first lady in Albany on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you going to debate your Democratic primary opponent?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, I'm focused on the campaign that New Yorkers expect
to see between me and my (Republican) opponent. There is still
another federal court challenge on the other matter, so my focus is
really on talking about what I'll do in the Senate and pointing out
the differences between me and Congressman Lazio on issues that are
important to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why wouldn't you debate a Democratic opponent? You have one.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, you still have a federal court challenge that is going
on about who's going to be on that ballot. We're going to wait and
see how that plays out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Then you will debate if there's one, or not?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm going to stay focused on the election that is really
mattering to New Yorkers and the one that we're all engaged in and
that is the difference between Republicans and Democrats and
between me and my opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you will not debate?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're going to focus on this election. We're going to focus
on the issues that are important to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you don't want to give us a yes or no on whether you'll
debate him?
</P>
<P>
   A: We'll wait and see how all these court challenges play
themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with her poll numbers largely stagnant at under 50
percent support for months, Clinton recently challenged Lazio to a
series of debates.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, the Lazio campaign jumped on the McMahon bandwagon,
charging in one news release that ''Hillary Hypocrisy Hits
Hindenburg Heights.'' Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal Col fumed:
''Hillary Clinton needs to realize that New Yorkers don't coronate
their senators.''
</P>
<P>
   But the first lady's campaign, apparently concerned about being
embarrassed in the primary by McMahon, has chosen to ignore him.
The extent of his campaign has been one recent swing across the
state and as many media interviews as he can get.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican who switched to the Democratic Party in 1997,
McMahon said he doesn't understand ''why she would somehow be
afraid to debate me. All I am is a citizen of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clinton's Democratic allies tried to make it even
tougher for McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Democrats also filed petitions with the state Board
of Elections seeking to get into the primary. All lacked the 15,000
signatures needed. The two Republican members of the four-member
board voted to invalidate the four petitions, a move that would
have put Clinton and McMahon in a head-to-head primary. But the two
Democratic members of the board abstained, denying the third vote
needed to invalidate the petitions. That left a six-way primary, a
dilution of any anti-Clinton vote and less chance for McMahon to
embarrass her.
</P>
<P>
   A state judge subsequently invalidated the four petitions, but
the federal courts are also considering the situation and could
restore any or all of the four to the primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Marc Humbert has covered New York politics for The Associated
Press for more than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 1106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
