<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-NY--Travel-Historic Highway  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Heading from east to west, here are some of U.S.
Route 20's
highlights:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -The first formal Shaker Society settlement in America was
started in the Mount Lebanon area.
</P>
<P>
   -The oldest unaltered Episcopal church in the state, built in
1789, is located in Duanesburg.
</P>
<P>
   -In Sharon Springs, the derelict shells of once-majestic hotels
still stand as a silent reminder of the days when tourists came by
the thousands to bathe in the area's natural sulfur and magnesium
springs.
</P>
<P>
   -Cherry Valley was the scene of a famous massacre in 1778 in
which nearly 50 villagers and soldiers were killed by raiders led
by Joseph Brant, a prominent Iroquois chief. A large marble
sarcophagus commemorates the attack.
</P>
<P>
   -Richfield Springs is the home of the Petrified Creatures Museum
of Natural History, chartered in 1934 as one of the oldest hands-on
museums in the state. Visitors can dig for 40 different kinds of
invertebrate fossils on the museum's nearly six acres, which also
include woodland trails, nature paths and life-size dinosaur
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   -In Sangerfield, travelers pass the northern tip of Nine Mile
Swamp, which once served as the hiding place for the infamous
Loomis Gang, which terrorized the countryside from 1848-1866.
</P>
<P>
   -Bouckville, where one of the largest antique shows in the
Eastern United States is staged every August. Nearby is Nichols
Pond, where Samuel de Champlain and an expeditionary force of
French and Hurons attacked a stockaded fort of the Oneida Indians
in October, 1615 - an act that helped drive the Iroquois tribes to
ally with the English during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   -Cazenovia was a stagecoach stopover where John Lincklaen built
the Lorenzo House in 1807, an exquisite two-story Georgian
structure that features delicate pilasters, elliptical arches,
gables and a roof parapet.
</P>
<P>
   -Between Pompey and Lafayette, travelers cross the heart of the
ancient Onondaga Indian Nation where the centuries-old Iroquois
Confederacy was born. The area also is one of the leading
apple-producing areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   -In Cardiff, visitors will learn the history of the Cardiff
Giant, a 10-foot tall hand-carved statue that was buried in the
ground by two 19th-century local hucksters and became regarded as
''America's Greatest Hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   -As travelers pass through Auburn, they can stop at the homes of
Harriet Tubman, who became a national heroine for her pivotal role
in leading slaves to freedom through the Underground Railroad, and
former Secretary of State William H. Seward, who engineered the
purchase of Alaska from Russia in 1867.
</P>
<P>
   -Montezuma Swamp, a national wildlife refuge and a birdwatchers'
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   -In Seneca Falls, the birthplace of the women's suffrage
movement, visitors can stop at the National Women's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   -Waterloo boasts it is the birthplace of the first Memorial Day
observance. It also is the location of the Scythe Tree. Legend says
that in 1861, James Wyburn Johnson, a local farm boy, hung his
scythe on a six-inch poplar sapling until his return from the Civil
War. Johnson was killed in battle and scythe remained while the
tree grew. Today only six inches of blade shows; the wooden handle
having long ago rotted away.
</P>
<P>
   -Geneva is the home of the acclaimed Lake Geneva Inn and the
site of an old Iroquois village. It lies in the heart of the Finger
Lakes region and New York's wine country.
</P>
<P>
   -Town Line is remembered for the fact that a majority of the
townsfolk voted in 1861 to join the South and seceded from the
Union.
</P>
<P>
   -After passing through the Cattaraugus Indian Reservation,
travelers come to Westfield, the original headquarters of the Welch
Grape Juice Company, started in 1896 by Dr. Thomas Branwell Welch
and his son.
Sources: Preservation League of New York, American Guide Series:
New York
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 1340 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For New York's Democratic delegates, first lady is a boost  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - Four years ago, New York Democrats
practically limped to the convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Party faithful were still licking their wounds after losing the
governor's mansion to George Pataki. Republican Rudolph Giuliani
held the reins in New York City. And the GOP takeover of Congress
had weakened the state's Capitol Hill clout.
</P>
<P>
   This year, New York's 294 Democratic delegates head to Hollywood
with a bona fide star of their own - Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates say excitement over the first lady's U.S. Senate
candidacy - fresh off a spurt of other New York Democratic
victories - restores some needed luster to the state party.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were such a dispirited group in 1996 having lost so much.
There is nothing like winning to give a party energy and this time
around we are energized,'' state Party Chairwoman Judith Hope said.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where Democrats outnumber Republicans by an almost
5-3 margin, the loss of Gov. Mario Cuomo, a party icon, to the
unknown Pataki was a watershed event. The state Democratic Party
was broke and in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas native Judith Hope took over as chairman in 1995 and
gradually the party pulled itself out of the red and began a
grassroots campaign to reinvigorate support.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery saw results when in 1998 Democrats won three out of
four statewide races. Then-Rep. Charles Schumer defeated veteran
GOP Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, Eliot Spitzer edged out Attorney General
Dennis Vacco and Democratic Comptroller H. Carl McCall cruised to
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, at least, Clinton has the spotlight in New
York. That is especially true since the state is considered a lock
for Democratic presidential hopeful Al Gore, even more so after he
picked Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his running mate.
Lieberman is certain to appeal to New York's critical Jewish voting
bloc.
</P>
<P>
   ''All eyes are on the Senate race in New York because that's the
race that's close,'' Quinnipiac College pollster Maurice Carroll
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the first lady is only spending a few days at the
convention in Los Angeles the crowds she is drawing and the cash
she is raising rival what Gore will see when he arrives later in
the week. What other U.S. Senate candidate scores a guest spot on
the Jay Leno Show, as the first lady did Friday night?
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly we were without a star for a while. Now we've got a
world class star in Hillary Clinton,'' Hope added.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans scoffed at that that, taking a swipe at Clinton's
non-New York roots and her prolific fund raising among West Coast
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, she's a rented star because she's not a New Yorker,
state GOP spokesman Dan Allen said. ''With all the money she has
pouring in from Hollywood I guess she's going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the attention lavished on the first lady also
spills over onto New York's second-largest-in-the-nation
delegation. Besides the first lady's Monday night speech, a slate
of other New Yorkers will be featured on the stage of the Staples
Center - although not in coveted prime-time slots.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer and Reps. Charles Rangel, Carolyn Maloney
and Carolyn McCarthy are all speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Yorkers will be very visible in Los Angeles,'' predicted
state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, who is leading the
delegation. ''Hillary Clinton helps that, of course, but New
Yorkers by nature are not shy.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's delegates range in age from their 20s to 88. Most are
either Jewish or Catholic. The delegation is heavy on union members
and local lawmakers and even includes its very own supermodel.
Christie Brinkley, a party activist and fund raiser, is a delegate.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press survey of many of the state's delegates
found that most ranked health care as their number one concern,
education was second and the economy third.
</P>
<P>
   State parties were instructed by the Democratic National
Committee to select delegates that reflected the actual ethnic
breakdown of their state, and on this New York was close to the
mark.
</P>
<P>
   The state's delegates are 58 percent white 26 percent African
American, 12 percent Latino and 4 percent Asian. There is one
American Indian. Five percent of the delegates are gay or lesbian.
Half are male and half female.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates will be wined and dined at an endless string of
receptions with a well-known list of corporate sponsors. The first
fete, Sunday night's opening reception for the New York delegation,
is sponsored by Kodak, the state's largest employer.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said he did not feel such corporate sponsorship was
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Kodak's way of advertising, getting their name out there
for a relatively inexpensive price,'' he said. ''They are being
good corporate citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
