<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controversy emerges over treatment of infants born with ambiguous genitals </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - When Cheryl Chase was born in New Jersey in
1956, the doctors ''kind of freaked out.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They wouldn't let my mother see me and they wouldn't tell her
why,'' she said. ''After three days they decided to tell her that I
was a boy but I was terribly deformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase was what doctors call an ''intersex'' baby - meaning she
had ambiguous sexual organs. At least one in 2,000 infants is born
this way, with genitals that do not match their chromosomes or do
not conform to either male or female norms.
</P>
<P>
   In Chase's case, she was raised briefly as a boy, then - after
surgery - as a girl. It has been common for doctors to operate as
soon as possible on such infants, in some cases turning boys into
girls with surgery and female hormones. Traditionally, parents were
told to keep the operation a secret, even when the child grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the practice of early surgery - performed long
before the child can understand - is being questioned. Some
doctors, prompted by angry former patients, are urging a moratorium
on genital surgery that they regard as cosmetic. However, no
consensus yet exists as to when genital surgery is cosmetic and
when it is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something that I think is going to be argued for a long
time,'' said Dr. Justine Schober, a pediatric urologist in Erie,
Pa., who opposes much of the surgery done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Chase did not learn of her history until age 22 when she finally
succeeded in obtaining her medical records. She learned she had
been raised as a boy for a year and a half, after which her parents
''found their way to some doctors who were newly minted specialists
in intersex.''
</P>
<P>
   She was diagnosed as a ''true hermaphrodite'' with ovo-testes -
gonads containing both ovarian and testicular tissue. She also had
a uterus, a vagina and ''pretty typical female genitals except for
a large clitoris.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They determined that I had ovaries and could get pregnant,''
Chase said. ''Then they closed my abdomen and cut off my clitoris.
... They told my parents that they had discovered that I wasn't
really a boy but I was a girl. ... They told them they should
change my name, move to another town and not tell anyone where they
had gone.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning her past, Chase founded the Intersex Society of
North America in 1993, hoping to end the shame and secrecy
surrounding intersex and halt the type of surgery that had left her
scarred and unable to have an orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the second half of the 20th century doctors have treated
intersex as something that is so freakish that it renders the
intersex person ineligible for membership in society,'' she said.
''And because it is so freakish, ordinary ethics don't apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Danette Ivey is trying to help others who, like her, were born
with congenital adrenal hyperplasia, or CAH, an enzyme deficiency
that can be fatal without regular doses of steroids. The condition,
the most common intersex diagnosis, often causes a baby girl's
genitals to be ''virilized'' - to look something like a boy's.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1966 in Lubbock, Texas, Ivey had nine surgeries. She
says some were necessary - her urethra had to be repositioned - and
some not - her clitoris was either removed or ''buried so far that
it's not even possible to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You feel totally violated,'' she said. ''You lose all control
of your body because you have your parents and the doctor saying
'we're doing this to make you normal.' In my mind I was normal
until they started cutting on me.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of my life I wished I was dead,'' said Ivey, who lives
outside of Houston where she runs an Internet message board for
people with CAH and delivers pizza for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Her message to parents contemplating genital surgery for
children is: ''Don't do anything that is not medically necessary.
Let the child decide when they are older. Because once you do the
surgery you can't go back.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been medical practice since the 1950s to operate on a boy
who has a penis that doctors feel will be too small for intercourse
or a girl whose clitoris is regarded as too long.
</P>
<P>
   Medical textbooks say that at birth the penis should be at least
an inch long. If it's not, doctors remove the penis and testicles
and administer female hormones. The child is then raised as a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors would reduce the size of a girl's clitoris if it's more
than 3/8 inch long. They also may enlarge a girl's vagina if they
think it will not comfortably accommodate a penis when she grows
up.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of CAH, the clitoris sometimes ''looks like a little
penis,'' said Dr. Ian Aaronson, a pediatric urologist at the
Medical University of South Carolina and the chairman of the North
American Task Force on Intersex.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most mothers intuitively say, 'Well, she doesn't look like a
little girl,''' Aaronson said. ''Most doctors would feel
uncomfortable leaving children with grossly ambiguous genitalia, to
grow up through school with something unusual between their legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Lee, a pediatric endocrinologist at Hershey Medical
Center in Hershey, Pa., said he strives for ''a balanced
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My position would be that if the clitoris is enlarged but
still has the structure of a clitoris, that one ought not to rush
into surgery,'' Lee said. But he said surgery may be indicated
''when the genitals are such that they do not look female or
male.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee conceded that years ago, doctors operating on a child's
clitoris made scant effort to spare nerve endings and preserve
orgasmic potential. ''The big emphasis was on the appearance of the
genitalia,'' he said. ''Sadly so.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, he said, ''I'm confident that there is a better
result.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less confident.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is we have no long-term outcome studies, so we
really don't know if surgery hurts or helps,'' said Schober, the
urologist from Erie, Pa. ''It may normalize appearance, but there's
more to sexuality than appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice of assigning female sex to boys with small penises
was pioneered by sexologist John Money at Johns Hopkins Medical
Center in Baltimore. It is easier to create a vagina and labia than
enlarge a penis, and Money believed gender in infancy was so
malleable that a genetic male consistently raised as a girl would
adapt to life as a female.
</P>
<P>
   The theory gained a boost from one highly publicized case of a
boy who was changed to a girl in 1967 after his penis was destroyed
in a botched circumcision. Money described the child as a typical,
well-adjusted little girl.
</P>
<P>
   The theory was discredited when that child, now an adult named
David Reimer, disclosed that he had reassigned himself as a male at
age 14 and was married and living happily as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, the pediatric endocrinologist, said that when he received
his medical training in the late 1960s and early '70s ''the
recommendation was to reassign the sex of a boy with micropenis,''
but he thought the practice had gone out of fashion in the last 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. William Reiner, a psychiatrist and pediatric urologist
at Johns Hopkins, said it is still going on, even though recent
research indicates that men with small penises can function quite
well as males.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner said he has found 36 children who were castrated and
assigned as girls either in his practice or in his research, and
two-thirds of them have switched back to being boys.
</P>
<P>
   He said that once the child is told what happened, ''not only
does the child himself recognize that he was male, but often his
classmates have always recognized he was male.''
</P>
<P>
   Schober said textbooks still recommend raising a boy with a
small penis as a girl.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the 1992 edition of Campbell's Urology advises
that ''if the penis does not respond to testosterone, gender
reassignment probably should be performed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like a quick fix,'' said Schober. ''A quick, easy
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase added, ''Part of the problem is that (doctors) wanted a
simple answer by which they could use the tools they like to use,
which is medical intervention and surgery, to make this go away.''
</P>
<P>
   These days the treatment of intersex children is in such a state
of flux that parents get opposite advice depending on which doctor
they consult.
</P>
<P>
   When Kelley Schultz's twins were born in 1998 she didn't notice
anything odd about her daughter Madison's genitals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't think I really knew what they were supposed to
look like,'' said Schultz, a corporate meeting planner from the
Seattle area. ''I never thought anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But at 6 months Madison was diagnosed with CAH. (Her twin
brother was not affected.) She had a mild case, but a team of
specialists at Children's Hospital in Seattle determined that her
clitoris was too large and she should have surgery to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
   ''My pediatrician was really against it,'' said Schultz, who
agreed to have the surgery performed when Madison was 18 months.
''It was a really hard decision because there wasn't anything wrong
with her in her functioning. ... But it did not look normal, and
they could fix it, so why not fix it?''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ''I think it's fine if a child has big ears or a
funny-looking nose, but I think that when you are dealing with
sexuality and those type of things, if you wait for your 13- or
14-year-old child to make that decision, there could already be
psychological damage done.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherie, a Californian who asked that her last name not be used,
gave birth in 1993 to a son with a small penis, undescended
testicles and no fully formed scrotum. It took three or four weeks
to determine that he had XY chromosomes and was a genetic male.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie said one ''crotchety old urologist'' suggested raising
the baby as a girl. But he was overruled by doctors at the
University of California at Davis who advised that ''there's no
reason to turn this child into a girl just because he has a small
penis.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherie, who counsels other parents through the Ambiguous
Genitalia Support Network, said her son is a happy 7-year-old boy
but if he decides to be a girl later on that will be up to him.
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal,'' she said, ''is for everyone to do what's in the
best interest of the child, to put the needs of their child ahead
of everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Intersex Society of North America, http://www.isna.org
</P>
<P>
   CAH Our Stories and Our Voices, http:cahourstories.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
