<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gibbs was last surviving founder of American Diabetes Association  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Dr. Charles Brooke Flint Gibbs, one of 32
founders of the American Diabetes Association, has died.
</P>
<P>
   He was 105. Gibbs died in his sleep Aug. 2. He had been the last
surviving founding member of the 60-year-old American Diabetes
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs practiced medicine in Rochester from 1921 to 1980, in
later years becoming the oldest living physician in Monroe County
and the oldest living alumnus of the Syracuse University College of
Medicine, having graduated in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs made daily house calls over 59 years. When he retired on
Jan. 1, 1980, he wrote each patient a personal letter and met with
each to recommend another doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs was born Sept. 27, 1894, in Black River, Jefferson County.
His father was a cabinetmaker. His mother was a teacher and
part-time reporter for the Watertown Times whose pay, 5 cents per
column inch, helped put Gibbs and his younger brother through
medical school.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1920s, he worked with pioneering diabetes researcher
John Murlin, whose University of Rochester team was trying to
isolate insulin. They were narrowly beaten by University of Toronto
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, the year the University of Rochester's medical school
was founded, Dr. Gibbs opened the area's first clinic for
diabetics, at Rochester General Hospital. The next year, he became
chief of Strong Memorial Hospital's first diabetes clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The Charles B.F. Gibbs Library at the University of Rochester
serves the endocrinology department.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs is survived by three children, 12 grandchildren, and 14
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held at 2 p.m. Aug. 23 at the Third
Presbyterian Church, 4 Meigs St. Burial will be private.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
