<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Deal Disillusions Burundians  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- Like many Burundians, Generose Gasinzi
was hopeful when peace talks began between the Tutsi-led government
and the Hutu rebels. She thought it could mean an end to the
country's 7-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But with fighting continuing and both sides saying they can't
reach a deal by the Aug. 28 signing deadline set by former South
African President Nelson Mandela, the 35-year-old Tutsi government
employee has lost all hope that peace is forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's tense and people are worried,'' said Gasinzi, who has
lost friends and relatives to the conflict. About 200,000 people
have been killed since 1993, when Burundi's first free elections
collapsed amid ethnic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Burundi knows that power-sharing is the only way to
end the war. Any proposal must both end the Hutu rebellion and
ensure that the minority Tutsis can yield their grip on the army,
government and economy without fear of persecution.
</P>
<P>
   But as in all peace agreements, the details and the spirit are
what matter most.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having a document is irrelevant if we don't share a common
vision,'' said Terence Nahimana, a Hutu member of parliament. ''In
advanced societies, whoever is in power doesn't affect whether my
children will go to school. In Burundi, our children going to
school will depend on the people in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Since independence from Belgium in 1962, the Tutsi minority has
gradually assumed control of the country following several abortive
Hutu uprisings. Burundi's lucrative tea and coffee exports have
been largely controlled by the Tutsi elite, who don't want to lose
their privileged positions.
</P>
<P>
   For middle-class public servants like Gasinzi, the fear of Hutu
domination is real. When Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu, won Burundi's
first democratic elections seven years ago, many of her Tutsi
colleagues lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   When news spread that Ndadaye had been assassinated by Tutsi
paratroopers, her uncle was lynched in Kamenge, a mixed
neighborhood in the nation's capital. Hutu militia fighters set up
roadblocks and started expelling the Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
   Many Hutus insist they have been victims of a Tutsi-controlled
political system that has oppressed them for decades and that
robbed them of the 1993 vote. They accuse the Tutsi-dominated army
of killing their friends and families in revenge for rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In recent fighting, 50 Hutu civilians were killed in a church
and 27 army cadets died in an ambush.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 Burundian political parties and interest groups meeting
in Arusha, Tanzania, this coming week to work out a peace deal have
split into Hutu and Tutsi blocks. They have been unable to agree on
who will lead a three-year transition period up to new elections.
</P>
<P>
   They also disagree about whether to call the 1993 killings of
Tutsi civilians a genocide orchestrated by Hutu authorities -- an
important political admission demanded by Tutsis. Hutu negotiators
have balked at the suggestion, hoping instead to free 11,000 Hutu
prisoners the government says are responsible for the killings.
Hutu rebels consider the prisoners political detainees.
</P>
<P>
   The army also insists that a cease-fire should precede the
signing of any deal. The rebels want one to come after the
agreement is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Nahimana said most of the energy at the talks has been wasted on
individuals jostling for positions.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is competition for power in the presidency, parliament
and government. But there is no cooperation,'' Nahimana said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasinzi, meanwhile, has lost patience with the talks and the
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have seen everything so far -- a Hutu president, army coup,
politicians lying to our faces,'' she said. ''What can happen that
hasn't happened so far?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
