<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumer: give consumers credit rating access  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer, noting that some New
Yorkers pay as much as $60,000 more than necessary over the course
of a 30-year mortgage loan, called Saturday for consumers to
receive access to their credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, D-N.Y., announced plans for right-to-know legislation
that would allow consumers to review their credit ratings before
taking out a home loan.
</P>
<P>
   The result would be twofold, he said: It would allow consumers
to verify that credit information was correct, and it would give
them leverage in securing a better loan rate.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, thousands of New Yorkers with excellent credit pay
between $140 and $175 more per month than necessary on their
mortgages because they're unaware that they qualify for lower cost
loans. Consumers currently cannot review their credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation will lift the veil of secrecy over credit
scores and create greater opportunity for securing a home mortgage
at considerably less expense,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   For a home owner paying $175 extra per month on a mortgage, that
totals up to $60,000 in unnecessary payments over the course of a
typical 30-year loan.
</P>
<P>
   The Schumer bill is based largely on bipartisan legislation
recently approved by the California state assembly's banking
committee. Schumer's legislation would require all lenders to
provide a credit rating to each loan applicant, with an explanation
of how the rating was calculated.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's call for legislation was supported by both consumer
advocates and realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Realtors believe that every citizen should enjoy the
fundamental right to review the results of the mathematical
modeling that determine the award of a home mortgage,'' said Lee
Verstandig of the National Association of Realtors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 1415 </TRAILER>
