<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes Saudi Arabia, Kuwait  </HEADLINE>
By WAIEL FALEH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq's two highest councils met Saturday
with President Saddam Hussein and blasted Kuwait and Saudi Arabia
for continued aggression against Iraq, the official Iraqi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting discussed how to ''expose the aggression which
destroys Iraqi properties with American backing and Saudi-Kuwaiti
support,'' said a statement after the meeting of the Regional
Command of the al-Baath ruling party and the Revolutionary Command
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has criticized Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, along with Turkey,
for allowing American and British allies to use their bases for
daily flights over the no-fly zones of northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq also blames Kuwaitis and Saudis for the U.N. sanctions
imposed on its 22 million people since 1990. ''The Saudis are first
in aggression followed by the Kuwaiti rulers in treason,'' said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting said the aggression must be exposed to
''international and Arab public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's high-level meeting took place one day after two
people were killed and 19 injured in an allied airstrike on the
city of Samawa, 270 kilometers (168 miles) south of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq says allied airstrikes have killed over 300 citizens and
injured over 900 others. The allies dispute these figures.
</P>
<P>
   An official of the Air Defense Command said the strikes only
served to injure ''more innocent civilians.'' He said many
government offices, including a police building, were bombed in the
Friday evening airstrike.
</P>
<P>
   INA reported that the bombing also hit the main food ration
distribution center and six homes.
</P>
<P>
   The news agency said the Friday strikes were in response to
Saddam's Tuesday speech in which he said his Gulf neighbors had
''sold their souls'' to the United States and Israel. An unnamed
military spokesman said the strikes ''show how deep the conspiracy
is'' between Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and the allies.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Saturday to the United Nations, Foreign
Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf accused the Saudi and Kuwaiti
governments of ''providing logistical support for the American and
British forces, making them contributing partners in the
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister demanded that the U.N. Security Council
''rise up to its responsibilities in keeping the international
security and peace by stopping the continued aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   He also renewed Iraq's rejection of the no-fly zones, saying
they violate national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have been enforcing zones since
the end of the 1991 Gulf War. The zones were set up to protect
Shiite Muslim rebels in the south and Kurdish insurgents in the
north from attacks by Iraq's army.
wf-ts
</P>
</TEXT>
