<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HOLD FOR RELEASE 6:30 p.m.  </HEADLINE>
By CAROL TRAPANI AND MARY BETH PFEIFFER
Poughkeepsie Journal
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - The wait for organ transplants has
grown significantly in New York state, as organ donations fail to
keep pace with a growing demand for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 9,616 organ transplants in the state, the
Poughkeepsie Journal found that patients waited about 200 days
longer in 1998 than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The average waiting time for those who received transplants in
1998 was 485 days - about 1.4 years, according to a computer
analysis of records provided by the United Network for Organ
Sharing, which coordinates organ transplants under a contract with
the federal government. UNOS records included waiting times for
about 80 percent of transplanted patients.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found:
</P>
<P>
   -The wait grew most for people receiving liver transplants,
rising more than 300 percent, from 60 days in 1990 to 254 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   -Waiting times rose 60 percent for kidneys, the most common
organ transplanted, often from living donors, to 680 days in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   -Heart recipients waited 88 percent longer - 263 days in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   -Patients also waited longer for less commonly transplanted
organs such as lungs and pancreases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Waiting times have gone up really across the board,'' said
UNOS Spokesman Joel Newman. New York has the longest wait
nationally for kidneys among blood type O and A patients, who
comprise 80 percent of recipients, according to a 1999 report by
the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   The number of transplants at medical centers statewide grew 58
percent, from about 800 in 1990 to 1,300 in 1998. But as science
and medicine have improved the odds for transplant patients, the
number of organ donations has remained flat - at about 5,800 donors
from cadavers a year nationwide. That leaves many patients waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just don't have enough organs,'' said Dr. Ashok Shah,
medical director of renal services at St. Francis Hospital in
Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, more than 4,000 people on transplant waiting lists
nationwide died because there weren't enough donated organs.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, approximately 7,000 people are waiting for an
organ transplant, among roughly 70,000 Americans waiting
nationwide. Thousands more wait for corneal, bone and other tissue
transplants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
