<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More British Pigs Face Slaughter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Thousands more pigs could be slaughtered as
British authorities work to contain an outbreak of swine fever,
agriculture officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Some 6,000 animals have been killed already, and Belgium, Spain
and the Netherlands have imposed a ban on the import of British
pigs that is expected to last for several weeks. The moves come
after cases of swine fever were found on three farms in eastern
England this week.
</P>
<P>
   Pigs on five other farms linked to the breeding unit where the
disease is believed to have originated will also have to be killed,
the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food said.
</P>
<P>
   Swine fever is lethal to pigs but harmless to humans. It killed
millions of pigs in mainland Europe during the 1990s, but the
British cases are the first here in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 percent of Britain's pig production is exported, mostly
to Europe, generating $190 million annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
