<HEADLINE> Shroud of Turin Displayed in Italy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TURIN, Italy (AP) -- The Shroud of Turin was unveiled Saturday,
beginning a two-month Holy Year display with a presentation before
6,000 young pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony, caretakers said they were open to new
scientific study of the 14-foot, 3-inch strip of linen, which the
faithful believe wrapped Christ after he was taken off the cross.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Church is not afraid of science,'' Turin Archbishop
Severino Poletto told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Italian TV broadcast live from the Turin cathedral as clerics
presented the icon in an aluminum and plastic frame before pilgrims
from around the world. Many of the pilgrims had just arrived for
Pope John Paul II's World Youth Day in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul was among those traveling to Turin last year for the
shroud's first public display in two decades. He said at the time
he believed more research should be done.
</P>
<P>
   Believers say the mysterious shroud bears the blood and imprint
of Christ, beaten, tortured and crucified. But a carbon dating test
ended in 1988 with a scientific team declaring that the shroud
apparently came from medieval times.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes have flourished since then on the validity of that
study and others, including one by researchers at The Hebrew
University. The latter study concluded last year that pollen and
plant images on the shroud showed it originated in the area around
Jerusalem sometime before the eighth century.
</P>
<P>
   The display ends Oct. 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
