<HEADLINE> Pope Welcomes Youth Day Volunteers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Upbeat and joking, Pope John Paul II on
Saturday welcomed more than 20,000 young volunteers lending a hand
with the coming crowds of next week's World Youth Day.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter with the blue T-shirt-clad volunteers brought a
rare series of smiles to the 80-year-old pontiff's face -- as well
as a rare papal plug. John Paul recognized an Italian catering
company that is helping to feed the 1.2 million-plus young pilgrims
expected here.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even the Pope's getting something out of it!'' John Paul said,
getting surprised laughs from the crowd. The Italian company
deserved note for taking care of the food, he said -- ''delicious!
At least, we think it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   World Youth Day is actually a week of events running from
Tuesday to Aug. 20. It has long promised to be a centerpiece of the
Roman Catholic Church's Holy Year, and with the energy and
enjoyment John Paul has always gotten out of young people, it
stands to be a highlight for the aging pontiff as well.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms similar to those of the neurological disorder
Parkinson's have drained much of the emotion from the pope's face
over the years. The woodenness makes the smiles and even grins that
young people -- squirming children or enthusiastic teens -- still
bring to the pope's face that much more noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul spoke at his summer palace at Castel Gandolfo, which
he will share with about 15 young pilgrims coming from Tahiti,
Congo, Sri Lanka, Canada and points in Italy for Youth Day. Giant
TV screens carried Saturday's greeting to other volunteers in St.
Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul started the youth day tradition in 1985, then took it
around the world. Other youth days have been held in Argentina,
Spain, Poland, the Philippines and France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
