<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New farm preservation revives issue of forced zoning for farmland  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman last week kicked off
a groundbreaking approach to how farms can be preserved in New
Jersey by letting town and county officials get more involved in
planning.
</P>
<P>
   But for some farm advocates, fear is creeping in over just whose
ground they intend to break.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of well-meaning people out there who don't
have a clue what the hell they are doing,'' said John Rigolizzo
Jr., a farmer and the elected president of the New Jersey Farm
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is designed to give towns or counties Planning
Incentive Grants, which go by the acronym PIG. These grants are
supposed to let local officials preserve lots of farms with less
money up front, provided the farms are located near or next to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Whitman signed the PIG law. Last Wednesday, she
signed the first bill to put PIG into effect, doling out $9.8
million in grants to 12 mostly rural towns.
</P>
<P>
   Rigolizzo said the Farm Bureau worked on the PIG law and
supports it. But he also said this new concept could create a
dangerous temptation for local officials to use zoning regulations
to specify where farms ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   While such zones might sound like common sense, farm advocates
say they are fatal to agriculture. Rigolizzo said changes in
land-use law that hurt the real estate value of a farmer's land can
drive him out of business. ''This is something we are watching very
closely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Republican lawmaker who thought up the program has
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Connie Myers, R-Hunterdon, said her goal was to
get more farmers enrolled in open-space preservation more quickly.
Eight of the 12 towns approved Wednesday for PIG funding are in her
legislative district.
</P>
<P>
   But since the enabling law was signed last year, she has had
worries about how the Whitman administration has been intending to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is the folks in the governor's office who came
from an environmental background, not an agriculture background,''
Myers said. ''They believe that zoning is the answer, not purchase.
They are focused on that, they are focused on maximizing that and
minimizing the spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said even Whitman's remarks as she signed the PIG funding
law were unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ''She never talked about the value of the program as I see it.
She talked about planning and preserving contiguous acres, but she
did not talk about acquisition up front,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rigolizzo admits there is no evidence the PIG law will lead to
new zoning laws. In fact, it is illegal in New Jersey to use
agricultural zoning to designate farmland. But similar steps can be
taken that have roughly the same effect, and farmers fear if this
occurs it will wreck the collateral value of their only business
asset.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers need land value to stay in business because they need
loans to stay in business, and their land is their collateral. Less
collateral forces the farmer to pay unaffordable interest rates,
provided they can even find a bank to give them a loan. ''Many
farmers pay more in interest every year than most people earn,''
Rigolizzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of land-value problems can snowball, prompting farmers to
sell to developers and get out while they can, even if the fears
are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Rigolizzo said the PIG program does specifically provide for
such zoning changes. On paper.
</P>
<P>
   ''The potential danger there is that you run into problems with
the local planning boards that might do something a little more
with it. They were always in the back of my mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, some 66,000 acres have been preserved through the
farmland preservation. The pace has accelerated sharply since
Whitman announced her open-space goal of preserving a million
acres, and now PIG is targeting another 14,000 acres of farms.
</P>
<P>
   Farms are preserved by changing the property deed to prevent
development. The farmer gets paid cash for this loss, keeps the
land and may continue to farm it or even sell it, as long as it
remains open. The collateral value of the land is reduced, but the
farmer gets an interest-earning cash reserve to compensate for it.
</P>
<P>
   Rigolizzo is a fifth-generation vegetable grower in Winslow
Township who began helping work his father's 400 acres 40 years ago
at age 7. He said few elected officials really understand farming,
and that few of his tractor-driving colleagues take the necessary
steps to make sure that their mayors and residential neighbors are
educated about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The average person who reads the paper on Sunday morning
hasn't the faintest idea of how we stay in business, what affects
our business,'' Rigolizzo said.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, farmers are not quick to sell to developers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people are afraid that farmers will pick up and go at the
drop of the hat if someone offers them the right price,'' Rigolizzo
said. ''But for the most part farmers are stubborn and eternally
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Most farmers would like to be able to stay on the farm until
the day they die. It is in their blood, it is in their life, and
you will take what Mother Nature throws at you as long as you can
send your kids to school, keep your wife in clothes and throw some
paint on the house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And ultimately it does make sense to have farming zones - as
long as zoning laws are not used to create them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you are farming a farm and you are surrounded by houses,
you are not going to be farming for long because people don't like
what you do, they don't like the dust, they don't like the
irrigation, they don't like that we use pesticides,'' Rigolizzo
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 1454 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor writes novel based on Delaware baby-dumping case  </HEADLINE>
By SEAN O'SULLIVAN
The (Wilmington) News Journal
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) - This month, a new book will hit stores
involving a suburban, middle-class teen-ager who faces the death
penalty after dumping her newborn in a trash bin in a small
Delaware town.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ''True Justice,'' is by Robert K. Tanenbaum, one of
the attorneys who represented Amy Grossberg, the suburban,
middle-class teen-ager from Wyckoff, N.J., who faced the death
penalty after she dumped her newborn in a trash bin in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   It is, according to the author, a work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Tanenbaum said he drew from a number of other baby-dumping cases
across the country, not just the story of Amy Grossberg.
</P>
<P>
   He said this book is meant to be a discussion of moral and
ethical implications. '''True Justice' deals with how these cases
should be handled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in Delaware?
</P>
<P>
   It just fit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This blend of fiction and Tanenbaum's real-life legal practice
is nothing new. Tanenbaum has written 13 other books based on his
legal career, which includes time as a New York prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys involved in the Grossberg case said they fully
expected Tanenbaum to write a book about the case at its
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   And with Amy Grossberg and one-time boyfriend and co-defendant
Brian Peterson Jr., also of Wyckoff, N.J., deciding to remain
silent since their release from jail earlier this year, it may well
be the last word on the case, which gained nationwide attention in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the book is written, Tanenbaum could be on
shaky ethical and legal ground, according to legal ethicists.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gilbert Johnston, dean of the John Marshall Law School in
Chicago, said Tanenbaum might be ''playing on the margin of the
spirit of the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though ''True Justice'' is labeled fiction, Grossberg could
have an ethics complaint against Tanenbaum if he discloses any
confidences or secrets, said John Corkery, a professor of law and
assistant dean at Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   However, from a description of the book, Corkery said he did not
see a clear breach of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Tanenbaum said he did not get the book approved by the
Grossbergs. ''I assume they will read it with the rest of
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he listens to his conscience when writing his
books. ''I don't clear them with other people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Tanenbaum said he still feels strongly about
Grossberg's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Although he agreed to a plea deal in which Grossberg admitted to
manslaughter, Tanenbaum maintains that prosecutors got it wrong. He
said Grossberg's baby was stillborn and that Grossberg was
suffering from seizures that rendered her incapacitated that night.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and investigators disagreed with his account.
</P>
<P>
   They described Grossberg as the driving force in the
relationship and said she was significantly responsible for the
events that led to the death of her son.
</P>
<P>
   Early on Nov. 12, 1996, Grossberg, then 18, called Peterson,
also 18, to drive to Newark from Gettysburg, Pa. The two went to a
motel room, where Grossberg gave birth to a baby boy. The baby was
then put in a trash bag and thrown into a trash bin behind the
motel.
</P>
<P>
   The pair were later caught, after Grossberg was taken to the
hospital with postnatal complications.
</P>
<P>
   After both reached plea agreements with prosecutors, a judge
cited Grossberg's apparent lack of remorse when sentencing her to
30 months in jail, six months longer than Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg was released May 10 after serving 24 months. Peterson,
who also pleaded guilty to manslaughter, was released Jan. 5 after
serving 17 months. Both received time off their sentences for good
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Tanenbaum said Grossberg's treatment was unusual and harsh
because Delaware Attorney General M. Jane Brady was playing
politics with the case, citing her appearance on the television
show ''Geraldo'' shortly after the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's office would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the description of Tanenbaum's book at Amazon.com,
the novel begins by following the story of New York district
attorney Butch Karp, a recurring character in Tanenbaum's work, who
is prosecuting a poor Hispanic girl for murder after she dumps her
baby in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   The plot takes a turn for the familiar, however, when Karp's
wife, Marlene, accepts her own private-practice client.
</P>
<P>
   That case ''takes her a few hundred miles south to a small
Delaware town, where another baby has been found, its lifeless body
placed in a motel trash bin by two scared kids. Marlene is
representing the mother, a doe-eyed, middle-class suburban teen who
claims the baby was stillborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complications come from ''a politically ambitious local
prosecutor who is pressing to make it a case of capital murder''
and the infant's father, who is ''singing a different song, placing
all of the blame on the girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanenbaum said he did not take the case for the purpose of
writing the book. He said the book grew out of his experiences in
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted desperately to try the case,'' said Tanenbaum, who
said he only relented because Grossberg's parents wanted to take
the safe route. When you go to a jury, he said, you never know what
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   So does he finally get to try the case in ''True Justice?''
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll have to read the book,'' Tanenbaum said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 1501 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two more New Yorkers test positive for the West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Two more Staten Island residents have contracted
the West Nile virus, but both were treated and are recovering at
home, health officials reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical that all New Yorkers, particularly the elderly
and those who live on Staten Island, take precautions to reduce
exposure to mosquitoes,'' city Health Commissioner Neal Cohen told
a City Hall news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced that a dead crow found in the East Tremont
section of the Bronx was infected with West Nile - the first sign
of the virus in that borough. In response, trucks are to spray
pesticides on Tuesday in a two-mile area where the bird was
discovered to try to destroy mosquitos that may be transmitting the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Test results for the 64-year-old woman and the 63-year-old man
came back positive on Friday. Another Staten Island resident also
was infected with the virus earlier this month, but the 78-year-old
man has made a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who lives in Great Kills, became ill with symptoms of
meningitis on Aug. 4. The 63-year-old man, from the Willowbrook
neighborhood, began showing signs of meningitis on July 31, and was
admitted to a hospital on Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Both were infected before the city started spraying last month,
since it takes up to two weeks for symptoms of appear. Staten
Island was last sprayed on Aug. 2, and the entire borough is
scheduled for another round on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is commonly carried by blood-sucking mosquitoes, which
transmit it through bites. Infection may result in encephalitis, an
inflammation of the brain, or meningitis, an inflammation of the
brain's lining and the spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen advised residents to wear protective clothing such as long
pants, long-sleeved shirts and socks while outside when mosquitoes
are active. The health commissioner also urged people to eliminate
pools of standing water where mosquitoes are likely to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, during the first known appearance of the West Nile
virus in the Western Hemisphere, seven people died and 62 others
were infected in the New York metropolitan area, prompting the city
to undertake an aerial and ground spraying campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The virus apparently survived the winter, in hibernating
insects.
</P>
<P>
   This year, health officials were ready with a huge preventive
effort: They have tested hundreds of birds and tens of thousands of
mosquitoes, while spreading insect repellant where infected birds
or mosquitoes were found.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to commend the New York City Department of Health for
its extensive surveillance activities, which have enabled us to
identify West Nile virus quickly and to take appropriate action as
needed,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the news conference were Richard Sheirer, director of
the Mayor's Office of Emergency Management, and Staten Island
President Guy Molinari.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus is named after the West Nile region of
Uganda, where it was was first isolated in 1937. West Nile virus is
most commonly found in Africa, West Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York State Health Department:
http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Centers for Disease Control and Prevention:
http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/westnile/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
