<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Envoy Denies Hostage Ransom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Despite signs of Libyan activity,
negotiators on Saturday denied reports that Libya has offered a $25
million ransom for hostages being held by a Muslim rebel group in
the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no truth to that,'' Abdul Rajab Azzarouq, Libya's
former ambassador to the Philippines, said about reports out of
Lebanon that Libya had made the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine government's chief hostage negotiator, Robert
Aventajado, also denied the reports. But both he and Azzarouq said
Libya has been involved in ''livelihood projects'' -- development
aid for Muslim communities in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Two major Muslim rebel groups have been fighting for years to
carve an independent nation out of the impoverished, heavily Muslim
southern Philippines. The smaller of the groups, the Abu Sayyaf,
seized 21 hostages from a Malaysian diving resort in April and
brought them to Jolo island in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   A German woman and six Malaysians have since been released, and
negotiators including Aventajado and Azzarouq have been working to
free the others.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, leading Beirut daily newspaper An-Nahar reported that
Seif al-Islam, Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi's son, sent an
emissary to Manila to try for a deal to end the hostage standoff.
</P>
<P>
   It said the envoy, Mohamad Ismail, contacted the Lebanese
Embassy in Tokyo and expressed ''full readiness'' to pay $1 million
ransom for the release of Marie Moarbes, a Lebanese-French woman,
as a first priority. The report said Libya would then pay $24
million for the rest of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The Beirut newspaper also said the freed hostages would be
encouraged to travel to Libya to thank the leadership for its
mediation -- a media show that Tripoli could use to improve its
international standing.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail, who is helping Azzarouq, denied the report.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's rubbish,'' he said, adding that it would be illogical to
give more than what the kidnappers had asked for. The Abu Sayyaf
rebels have demanded $1 million for each of the nine Western
hostages still in their hands -- two Germans, two Finns, Moarbes,
two other French, and two South Africans. The rebels are also
holding three French television journalists, three Malaysians and
two Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the denials, some other reports hinted at Libyan
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine Air Transportation Office said it had received an
inquiry from the Libyan embassy on flying a plane from Libya,
although no request for a permit has been made. And in Lebanon,
Prime Minister Salim Hoss' office said in a statement that an envoy
was instructed to ''head to Libya to welcome Marie (Moarbes) once
she arrives at Tripoli airport and to bring her back to Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Traboulsi was to leave for Libya Saturday but the trip was
canceled at the last minute and was not expected for another two
days, diplomatic sources said. And a chartered flight arranged for
Saturday by the Libyan Embassy in Beirut for the local press to
cover the release was also postponed until at least Monday,
indicating that a release was planned but had been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Since he became Libya's ruler in 1969, Gadhafi has been
supportive of Muslim, nationalist and leftist rebel groups around
the world. He has a long history of ties with Muslim rebels in the
southern Philippines, including sending development aid and trying
to help negotiate peace agreements between rebels and the
Philippine government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 1521 </TRAILER>
