<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VP Vote To Test Paraguay Democracy  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- More than a year after their vice
president was murdered, Paraguayans will pick his successor in a
special, one-office election that threatens to test this South
American country's wobbly democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials spent Saturday tending to final preparations
for the Sunday vote, which will install an elected vice president
alongside highly unpopular President Luis Gonzalez Macchi.
</P>
<P>
   Three candidates are vying to succeed Luis Argana, whose murder
in March 1999 forced former President Raul Cubas to resign and
prompted his chief political ally, a controversial former army
chief, to flee the country. Cubas was suspected of being involved
in Argana's death.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi took over, but his popularity has plummeted as Paraguay's
economy dips into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayans have never voted for a vice president outside of a
presidential election. Opposition members believe they now have
their best chance in years to break the stranglehold of the
Colorado Party, which has governed Paraguay since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Polls conducted this week show a virtual tie between the two
leading candidates, Julio Cesar Franco of the opposition Liberal
Party and Felix Argana, the son of the slain vice president and a
member of the Colorado Party. Running a distant third is Ricardo
Buman, an artist and candidate for the little-known Humanist Party.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what will happen when an unelected, unpopular
president is combined with someone the voters picked. Franco has
alluded to pushing Macchi from office, and some people here predict
that if the Colorado Party loses, their supporters could turn
violent.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a decade since a military coup toppled
Alfredo Stroessner's dictatorship, South America's longest-running
in the 20th century at 34 years. But the shaky democracy that
followed in the footsteps of the general's jackboots has hobbled
along from one crisis to another.
</P>
<P>
   The last 18 months has been no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Cubas, the first civilian president to succeed another in
Paraguay, was forced to resign and seek political asylum in Brazil.
His friend, Lino Oviedo, a former army chief, also fled and was
eventually arrested in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayan authorities want to question Oviedo in the Argana
case. He also is suspected of inspiring a May coup attempt --
Paraguay's third in four years -- by military officers known to be
sympathetic to him.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote carries significant undertones of the last year's
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, the opposition candidate, has made unapologetic appeals
to Oviedo supporters. If elected, the 48-year-old doctor has
suggested that he would work to have Macchi removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Argana supporters, meanwhile, have suggested that his election
to office would be a first step toward justice for his father's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Argana has cast himself as a stabilizing force in Macchi's
troubled administration. Macchi's popularity has dipped to less
than 20 percent as Paraguay struggles through a grinding recession.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope to bring some stability to this administration and to
the country,'' Argana told a gathered crowd of cheering supporters
in downtown Asuncion. ''We need to live in peace and work for the
economic betterment of Paraguay.''
</P>
<P>
   To Oviedo sympathizers, Argana had this to say: ''I don't want
the votes of those Colorados that have their hands dirtied with
blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 1528 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
