<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Fears Jerusalem Violence  </HEADLINE>
By SALAH NASRAWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- President Hosni Mubarak warned Saturday that
a compromise over Jerusalem would lead to uncontrollable violence
in the Middle East, and said no Arab or Muslim can relinquish
rights to east Jerusalem and its holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Egypt would not stop Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat from
reaching a deal over the disputed city, ''if it's compatible with
his Palestinian people's demands,'' Mubarak said in an interview
with the Cairo weekly magazine Rose El-Youssef.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any compromise over Jerusalem will cause the region to explode
in a way that cannot be put under control and terrorism will rise
again,'' Mubarak said in his first public comment since the
collapse of last month's talks between Arafat and Israeli prime
minister Ehud Barak. Mubarak is a key mediator in the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, Barak offered the Palestinians limited control
over parts of east Jerusalem, but Arafat held firm on the
Palestinian demand for full sovereignty. The traditionally Arab
area contains the third-holiest shrine in the Islamic world, the Al
Aqsa mosque on the Temple Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ''No single person in the Arab or Islamic world can squander
east Jerusalem or Al Aqsa mosque,'' Mubarak said. ''In this
context, even Arafat himself will not dare to sign a deal to give
up these Muslim sanctities.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we will not dictate to him any decision that he does not
accept and that is not compatible with his Palestinian people's
demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak's comments came amid reports that Arab leaders have been
cold to the idea of a special Arab summit called by Arafat to seek
support for his position in the peace negotiations. While Arabs in
principle back Arafat's refusal to compromise on east Jerusalem,
they show little enthusiasm to convene a summit that would be seen
as a platform to endorse the Palestinians' moves.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials have said Arafat is disappointed at the
lack of such support, badly needed whether or not he reaches an
agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have announced plans to declare an independent
state on Sept. 13, with east Jerusalem as its capital. Israel says
an undivided Jerusalem should be its ''eternal'' capital.
</P>
<P>
   However, after meeting with Norwegian officials, Arafat
indicated he might postpone the unilateral declaration of
statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was scheduled to meet with Israeli senior statesman
Shimon Peres in Oslo on Friday, but arrived well after the Sabbath
had begun. Peres said he had a ''long and warm conversation'' by
telephone with the Palestinian leader Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Peres and Norway's foreign minister indicated Saturday that
progress is being made toward the final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time is short. We must all do our best so the last gap does
not become a setback,'' Peres said after talks with Norwegian
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Foreign Minister Thorbjoern Jagland said he had a
clear impression from his talks with Peres and Arafat that both
sides are interested in an agreement and there was a ''good
possibility'' of a new Mideast peace summit soon.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, on the heels of a trip to 15 Arab and European countries
in 18 days, returned to the Middle East Friday. His envoys continue
to court support for the Palestinian position.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli envoys are also seeking support. Acting foreign minister
Shlomo Ben-Ami met officials in Spain on Saturday, along with
Palestinian officials. He will also visit Italy and the Vatican to
discuss the negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
