<HEADLINE> Ventura Regrets Religion Comment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura says he wishes he
hadn't granted an interview to Playboy magazine in which he
criticized organized religion.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came Friday during a closed meeting with a CIA
leadership group in a Capitol hearing room. Reporters were barred,
but a microphone was left on and WCCO-TV taped the session.
</P>
<P>
   ''Personally, I'll survive it, and I knew I would. But it was
very difficult for my family in light of what happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the November Playboy issue, Ventura ignited a firestorm by
saying organized religion was ''a sham and a crutch for weak-minded
people who need strength in numbers. It tells people to go out and
stick their noses in other people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura also said he was thinking about running for a second
term. But when he leaves office, he said he plans to change his
appearance and go into seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's printed schedule described the group as a
''Central Intelligence Agency leadership group,'' but did not
elaborate. Later, Ventura spokesman John Wodele said he would not
describe the group in any more detail ''with respect for the CIA
and their need to be anonymous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
