<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storm dumps 10 inches of rain on northern New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
By HANAH CHO
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 12 inches of rain barraged parts of northern New
Jersey on Saturday, flooding lakes and rivers and causing several
bridges to collapse, sending cars into the water but injuring no
one. Some residents were evacuated and others were told to stay in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy rains also forced the postponement of a wedding
ceremony that was to have taken place at a minor league baseball
park.
</P>
<P>
   The storm hovered over parts of Morris, Sussex, Hunterdon,
Bergen, Essex, Hudson, Passaic and Union counties through the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a flash flood watch until
Saturday night for counties throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   A flash flood warning was issued for Somerset and Hunterdon
counties, where officials were concerned that people might get
caught in rising flood waters on roads.
</P>
<P>
   In Sparta, where more than 12 inches of rain fell, a state of
emergency was declared. Emergency messages were broadcast on a
local radio station urging residents to stay in their homes until
further notice.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding caused bridges to collapse in Jefferson Township
and Ogdensburg, officials said. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police received reports of submerged cars and motorists stranded
on top of their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   At least 100 emergency personnel were working in Jefferson
Township, a police dispatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Other roads and bridges in the area were underwater, police
said, and emergency workers were putting up sandbags in
Branchville.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of Sparta, Ogdensburg, Lake Hopatcong and
Hardyston Township were evacuated, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding forced the closure of several roads in Morris and
Sussex counties, including Route 15 in Sparta and Jefferson
Township and roads in Roxbury and Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   Power wires were brought down in Sparta, where the storm was
centered for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   GPU said about 10,000 customers lost power in Flemington, Newton
and Dover. Spokeswoman Sue Hohenadel said crews were trying to
respond, but were having trouble reaching the customers because
many roads were washed out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our crews are waiting to get to people, but we can't,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 770 PSE&AMP;G customers in Bridgewater, Willingboro and
Florence lost power Saturday afternoon. Their power was expected to
be restored by 6 p.m. said spokesman Don Tretola. Most of the
outages were caused by lightning strikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding made for a very quiet Saturday at Jefferson Bagels
on Route 15 in Jefferson Township.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw absolutely no traffic for the last three or four
hours,'' said Muhammad Farooq. ''We had heavy rain from 9:30 a.m.
to 1:30 p.m. We have a lot of bagels left over.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm forced the Somerset Patriots to postpone a wedding
that was to have taken place at Commerce Bank Ballpark on Saturday
evening. Glenn and Jane Jannarone, of Neshanic, are scheduled to
renew their vows at a game between the Somerset Patriots and the
Aberdeen Arsenal on Sept. 2., the Patriots said.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service said excessive runoff from the storm would
cause flash flooding of small creeks and streams, country roads and
farmland along the banks of creeks and streams. Forecasters also
said heavy rains could trigger rock and mudslides in steep terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered heavy rainfall since Friday morning had left the
ground saturated in various places. More showers and thunderstorms
were expected Saturday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 1731 </TRAILER>
