<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Call For Neo-Nazi Party Ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- German politicians are stepping up calls for a ban
on a right-wing political party, one of the steps being considered
in Germany's attempts to stem an outbreak of neo-Nazi violence.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence agencies have enough information on the
extreme-right National Democratic Party of Germany, or NPD, for the
country's highest court to enact a ban, Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's intelligence coordinator, Ernst Uhrlau, said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A constitutional state must consistently use its instruments
to signal that right-wing extremism will not be accepted in
Germany,'' Uhrlau said in an interview to be published Sunday in
Welt am Sonntag newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Chief government spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye said the government
would support a ban if it is recommended by a group of federal and
state officials considering proposals concerning the NPD. The group
met in Berlin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Heye also emphasized that neo-Nazism was not only a problem in
eastern Germany, where unemployment and lack of exposure to
foreigners has fueled xenophobic sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have an all-German problem,'' Heye said in an interview to
be published Sunday in the Frankfurt Allgemeine newspaper. ''No
matter what the statistics on offenses show: the most spirited
arsonists all come from the west.''
</P>
<P>
   In Munich, about 3,000 people demonstrated Saturday against
right-wing violence at an event including city leaders and
entertainers. The justice minister of Bavaria added his voice to
those of other conservative leaders for an NPD ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are of the opinion that the NPD in large part is
responsible for this right-wing violence,'' Manfred Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the interior minister of Hesse state, Volker Bouffier,
warned in an interview Saturday with the Wetzlarer Neuen Zeitung
that attempts to curtail right-wing parties could be ''politically
counterproductive'' and only create martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in the western city of Bruchsal, members of
the NPD's leadership denied their party was connected to violence.
At the same time, about 150 people demonstrated there against the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Saturday that 38 people were taken into custody
following the first game of the German soccer league's season,
including 16 people who were singing banned right-wing songs and
greeting one another with ''Heil Hitler'' salutes. The arrests came
at the Friday night game between Borussia Dortmund and Hansa
Rostock.
</P>
<P>
   Police also said Saturday that they had arrested the main
suspect in the deadly beating of a homeless man. Authorities say
Gunnar Doege, 24, and three other right-wing teens believe homeless
people don't belong in society.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that a concert has been planned for this
fall in Berlin to combat right-wing violence. The event would be a
part of the national ''Show Your Face'' initiative against
neo-Nazis, which has been proposed by leaders from government and
the Central Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
