<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Diplomat Ben-Elisar Dies  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Eliahu Ben-Elisar, a veteran right-wing
politician who helped negotiate Israel's peace treaty with Egypt,
and later served as ambassador to Egypt, the United States and
France, died Saturday in Paris. He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Elisar's death of cardiac arrest came just after he and some
other right-wing diplomats had been recalled by Prime Minister Ehud
Barak. Ben-Elisar died as he was preparing to return home, the
Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ben-Elisar was a political opponent of Barak, the prime
minister praised the man who was Israel's first ambassador to
Egypt, saying Ben-Elisar ''poured content into the new peace
between the two states.''
</P>
<P>
   As a major figure in the office of then-Prime Minister Menahem
Begin, Ben-Elisar was closely involved in the negotiations with the
late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, the first Arab leader to make
peace with Israel, in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Radom, Poland, Ben-Elisar arrived in British Mandatory
Palestine in 1942 at the age of 10. His family perished in the Nazi
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years he served in the Mossad, the Israeli spy
agency, but he never spoke about his experiences there.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Israel, he joined the right-wing opposition Likud
party and represented it abroad as a delegate to the Zionist
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Begin appointed Ben-Elisar director general of the prime
minister's office when Likud came to power for the first time in
1977. He was later elected to parliament, where he served two terms
as chairman of the Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, appointed Ben-Elisar
ambassador to the United States in 1996 and to France in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak and the Labor party took power in 1999, Ben-Elisar
found himself representing peace policies with which he did not
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a bitter opponent of the Oslo agreement (with the
Palestinians),'' said his Likud party colleague Uzi Landau, who now
heads the Foreign Affairs and Defense committee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barak's foreign minister, David Levy, did not replace
Ben-Elisar. Levy was a defector from the Likud and Ben-Elisar had
supported him when he was still a contender for the Likud
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, however, Levy quit Barak's coalition because he
disagreed with the concessions that Barak offered to the
Palestinians at the Camp David summit. Within days, Barak informed
several right-wing diplomats that they were being recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Elisar leaves a wife, Nitza, and two adult children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 1815 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
