<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Alberto Seen Weakening  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Alberto, the first hurricane of the 2000 Atlantic
season, strengthened early Saturday but forecasters predicted it
would gradually weaken as it moved over cooler waters.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane was not expected to pose any threat to land as it
continued to move northeast over open ocean. Satellite estimates
indicated Alberto had maximum sustained winds peaking at 125 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could get caught up by the westerly winds and just become a
big storm with high winds in the western Atlantic,'' said Stacy
Stewart, a hurricane specialist at the National Hurricane Center in
Miami. ''If it stays over warmer water it will still remain a
significant hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberto's center was expected to pass north of the Azores
islands, west of Portugal, in coming days as a powerful storm
system. At 5 p.m. EDT, Alberto was located about 1,345 miles west
of the Azores.
</P>
<P>
   The center revised its outlook for the season Thursday by
predicting above-average activity: at least 11 named storms, seven
hurricanes and three major hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
