<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Gets $20M Retirement Deal  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney
was granted a $20 million retirement package from the oil services
company he is retiring from, a person familiar with the company's
plan said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The package exceeds what Cheney would have gotten under the
terms of his employment agreement with Dallas-based Halliburton,
Co., where he was chairman and chief executive for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The company's board approved the package July 26, the day George
W. Bush announced that the former defense secretary would be his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said that in leaving Halliburton, which paid him $1.3
million last year, he will ''take a bath'' financially.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old Cheney stood to reap millions more if he had
stayed until his contract expired in 2003. But the package is
generous nevertheless, said one observer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since he quit and they gave him more than he could have
expected, he's certainly gotten a good break,'' said Herbert
Alexander, professor emeritus of political science University of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton board members could not be reached for comment.
Cheney spokesman Dirk Vande Beek said the details were being worked
out. Cheney will retire from the company Aug. 16, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's campaign, which has portrayed Bush and
Cheney as beholden to the interests of the oil industry, jumped on
the news.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the major issues in this campaign, particularly in the
Midwest, is that Republicans are offering the Big Oil ticket,''
said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ''They'll turn the Oval Office
into the Oil Office.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director: ''The
American public should be pleased that they have a vice
presidential nominee who has been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Cheney's retirement package is ''very much in keeping''
with those given to other Halliburton executives. ''He has assured
the governor and the American people that he will comply fully with
all laws and regulations and that, when elected, he will act to
ensure there is no conflict of interest,'' Hughes said later.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney both have ties to the oil business. Bush ran oil
drilling ventures in Texas. Halliburton provides technology and
equipment to oil companies and major oil producing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said he plans to sell off his Halliburton stock and
divest his other financial holdings, but not until the Republican
ticket wins in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why not? I'm not on the government roll yet, I have no control
over policy,'' Cheney said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander called that unusual, saying most candidates place
their assets in a blind trust to avoid the appearance of a conflict
of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The board's vote let Cheney avoid a potentially costly aspect of
his employment contract, which said he would forfeit some of his
compensation if he retired before age 62 without the board's
permission, according to The New York Times, which first reported
the deal Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney spent 25 years in public service as a House member and in
White House jobs in the Nixon, Ford and Bush administrations.
Joining Halliburton in 1995, he became a wealthy man, earning an
average of $2 million a year and reaping lucrative stock options.
In May he sold 100,000 shares of stock for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Company financial reports show Cheney was entitled to at least
$2.1 million in deferred compensation when he left, plus millions
of dollars worth of the company's stock. Another perk was the
deferred compensation earned an interest rate of about 10 percent,
higher than the usual 7 percent most companies pay.
</P>
<P>
   The company could sweeten the total package with the board's
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney owns or has options on more than 1 million shares of
Halliburton stock. His portfolio's value depends on the reduced
price he pays for his options and the stock price when he sells it.
Halliburton stock closed Friday at $51 a shares; a million shares
were worth $51 million.
</P>
<P>
   By letting Cheney take early retirement, the directors allowed
him to keep $10 million worth of stock and options he would have
forfeited had he resigned, the company's public filings show. It
was not clear whether the $10 million was part of the retirement
package or in addition to it, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's package is not unique for the oil industry, which often
rewards retiring executives handsomely, especially when companies
do well and executives have spent a long career there.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, Alexander said the package is lucrative
considering Cheney spent only five years at Halliburton.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton plans to make an announcement next week, the source
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 1832 </TRAILER>
