<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama Holds Out Hope For Tibet  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS MCDONALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   QAZA, India (AP) -- From an ancient monastery in the Himalayas,
the Dalai Lama sent out a message of hope Saturday for Tibetans who
live under what he called aparthied-like conditions in China.
</P>
<P>
   The Bhuddist spiritual leader was joined in prayers by thousands
of Tibetans, Indians and foreigners who have gathered for a 15-day
ceremony in Key Gompa, a 1,000-year-old monastery near India's
border with Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at Tibet locally, the situation is hopeless,'' the
Dalai Lama told the congregation seated in a prayer hall festooned
with giant paintings of Tibetan deities. ''But globally, things are
changing. Internationally we are gaining support everywhere and the
spirit of the Tibetans is very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama was leading the 15-day Kalachakra initiation
ceremony at the monastery. He spoke for an hour and 45 minutes to
an assembly of Indian, Tibetan and western journalists.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during Saturday's meeting, he compared China to
apartheid South Africa, saying that the Chinese believed themselves
to be superior to the Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he hoped to visit Taiwan later this year, a move
sure to draw an angry response from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hoping perhaps within the year, I may have the opportunity
to visit,'' the Dalai Lama said. He said Taiwan combined economic
progress with functioning democracy and Buddhist spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, who was awarded the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize, fled
Tibet in 1959 with thousands of supporters after a failed revolt
against Chinese rule of the mountain region.
</P>
<P>
   He will stay at the remote monaster in Spiti, a valley high in
the Himalayas, until Thursday, when he returns to his base in
Dharmsala, in northern India. Asked if the location made him
homesick, the Dalai Lama joked that the high altitude had given him
dry lips and headaches. Key Gompa is 13,579 feet above sea level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
