<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Mexico Official Under Arrest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A judge has ordered Mexico's former tourism
secretary placed under house arrest as police continue to search
for him, news reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Eugenio Ramirez on Friday ordered 30 days of house arrest
for former Tourism Secretary Oscar Espinosa Villarreal in the first
corruption case against a Cabinet member in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors of Mexico City's opposition-led government accuse
Espinosa of embezzling $45 million while he was Mexico City mayor
from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Espinosa resigned Tuesday, hours after prosecutors said they
could not prosecute him until he stepped down from his post, which
would remove the immunity from prosecution he enjoys as a Cabinet
member under President Ernesto Zedillo. He was named to the post
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of pressing charges, prosecutors asked Espinosa to
testify Thursday before the city's magistrate. When Espinosa failed
to show, the city's district attorney's office ordered police to
locate him.
</P>
<P>
   His defense lawyer Alonso Aguilar Zinser told the national
network Televisa on Friday that Espinosa will tend to the matter
when it reaches the courts. He did not give Espinosa's location.
</P>
<P>
   Espinosa, a member of Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary
Party, which lost the mayor's office to the center-left Democratic
Revolution Party in 1997, has said the accusations are politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Espinosa's party lost the presidency for the first time
in 71 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
