<HEADLINE> Indian Troops Kill Four Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By WASBIR HUSSAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAUHATI, India (AP) -- Federal troops killed four separatist
guerrillas in India's northeastern Assam state on Saturday, while
another rebel group blew up a power station, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   Indian authorities said they had sent at least 50,000 troops
into the region to reinforce security amid fears of further rebel
attacks ahead of the country's Aug. 15 Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   A senior army officer said soldiers shot the four militants
during a pre-dawn raid at a hotel in eastern Assam's Tinsukia
district, 330 miles from Gauhati, Assam's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The dead rebels belonged to the outlawed United Liberation Front
of Asom (ULFA), who are fighting for independence from India, the
officer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The slain ULFA militants, including an explosives expert of
the outfit, were planning to stage violent acts in the area before
Independence Day on August 15,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The separatist rebels usually step up violence ahead of India's
Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, tribal Bodo militants triggered a powerful
explosion near Madhupur in Kamrup district, 36 miles west of
Gauhati, damaging a transformer and power line.
</P>
<P>
   Police attributed the blast to the National Democratic Front of
Bodoland (NDFB) and say they have arrested at least 40 people for
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Militants have warned that they would take ''stern action''
against those who take part in the Independence Day celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month in Assam, tribal Bodo and ULFA militants blew
up two trains, including a passenger train, killing 12 soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
