<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain Complete Western Tour  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT, Ariz. (AP) -- George W. Bush pledged Saturday to
''restore the military power of the United States'' as he and
former rival John McCain completed a three-day Western campaign
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Sen. McCain, R-Ariz., sounded military themes,
here in McCain's home state and earlier at a rally near a naval
complex in Everett, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   They were Bush's final campaign events before he steps out of
the spotlight for the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''This administration for seven years has squandered the
political capital of a previous administration,'' Bush told a
courthouse rally here. ''We will restore the military power of the
United States. We do so to keep the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, defeated by Bush in the Republican presidential
primaries, compared him to a conservative Arizona hero, the late
Sen. Barry Goldwater. McCain noted Goldwater had begun his 1964
presidential campaign from the same Yavapai County Courthouse were
he and Bush were speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''Barry Goldwater didn't win. But his spirit ... of
conservatism, of an inclusive party ... are here today'' in Bush,
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, with the aircraft carrier USS Abraham Lincoln as a
backdrop, Bush issued an appeal in Washington to those in uniform:
''Stay in the military, there's a new commander in chief coming.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain told that audience that patriotism and respect for the
military were gaining in the country.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former Navy pilot and Vietnam War prisoner of war,
said Bush would help lift ''the pay, the morale and the benefits''
of those in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have complete confidence'' in Bush, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on a dock in the Port of Everett across from a naval
terminal, Bush mixed his pledges of increased attention to the
military with implied criticism of President Clinton's role as
commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would work with Congress for a military that was
better paid, better equipped and better trained.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to have a military of high spirits,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated his support for a national defense against
ballistic missiles, a cut in nuclear arsenals and vowed he would
''not defend outdated treaties,'' a reference to the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is seeking to negotiate changes in
that treaty to allow a national missile defense. Conservative
Republicans have suggested the pact is null.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also promised to reverse a recent political trend and carry
the Pacific Northwest. Oregon and Washington have not voted
Republican in a presidential election since Ronald Reagan's 1984
landslide re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have a good chance. We have the right issues,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Bush has been implying that his rival, Vice
President Al Gore should do more to repudiate President Clinton's
ethical lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's affair with a White House intern and the impeachment
process were ''an embarrassment. I think most Americans think
that,'' Bush said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton revived the subject himself on Thursday when he told a
group of evangelical ministers he was trying to rebuild his life
after the ''terrible mistake'' that led to his impeachment in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor was spending Saturday night and part of
Sunday with McCain on McCain's ranch at Sedona, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hear it's a spectacular place,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only that, but he's going to have spectacular food,''
chimed in McCain, noting that he planned to do the cooking himself
-- chicken and ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was then to head for his 1,500-acre ranch near Waco, Texas,
and planned to stay there until after the end of the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect some good rest,'' he said. He said he doubted he'd
watch the convention on television: ''I don't have cable. I'm
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   In their joint appearances, Bush praised McCain as ''a patriot,
a hero and a friend of mine.'' And McCain said Bush would ''restore
dignity, honor and respect to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   However, despite their show of affection and reconciliation in
public, the two former rivals spent little time together during
their train and plane trips, aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
