<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers for newspaper move to withhold reporter's notes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - Lawyers for The Philadelphia Inquirer want
to bar a New Jersey rabbi from obtaining the notes of a reporter
who covered the investigation into the 1994 killing of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Inquirer lawyer Warren W. Faulk, in court documents filed
Friday, said any information gathered by reporter Nancy Phillips is
protected by New Jersey's so-called shield law, which was enacted
to prevent news reporters from being forced to testify or turn over
their notes.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Phillips has signed a statement invoking the
law and is refusing to disclose any information, including her
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk also wants to block lawyers for Cherry Hill, N.J., Rabbi
Fred J. Neulander from calling Phillips to appear at a Sept. 1
hearing before state Superior Court Judge Linda G. Rosenzweig.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's lawyers contend that Phillips, who was present when
a private investigator told Camden County Prosecutor Lee A. Solomon
that the rabbi hired him to kill his wife, ''crossed the line from
reporter to witness'' in her dealings with the investigator,
Leonard Jenoff, and became an agent for the Camden County
Prosecutor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff confessed his role in the killing to Solomon and county
homicide Detective Martin Devlin at an Audubon diner on April 28,
with Phillips present.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's lawyers, Dennis Wixted and Jeffrey Zucker, in court
documents have cited a report in which Devlin said Solomon had told
him on April 20 that Phillips ''had information concerning the
possible participation'' of Jenoff in the killing. That was eight
days before Jenoff confessed to Solomon and Devlin.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this allegation by Solomon is true, Phillips was already
acting on behalf of the state in delivering Jenoff on a silver
platter,'' the lawyers said, adding that she was acting as an
informant rather than a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   But Faulk disagreed. He said that report ''does not indicate in
any way'' that Phillips gave specific information to Solomon, and
suggested that Solomon may have inferred that Phillips had
information about Jenoff's possible involvement because of the
questions she was asking.
</P>
<P>
   ''The subpoena issued to Ms. Phillips is nothing more than a
'fishing expedition' - an unsanctioned and unlicensed attempt to
rummage through six years of a reporter's confidential and
privileged materials to see if they contain any information which
might be helpful to the defense,'' Faulk wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk said the shield law was designed to give extensive
protection to reporters and that Neulander's lawyers have ''failed
to satisfy the stringent statutory prerequisites for overcoming''
the privileges established by that law.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, charged with capital murder, is being held at the
Camden County jail. He is accused of arranging to have his wife,
Carol, killed at their Cherry Hill home. Prosecutors say he wanted
his wife dead so he could pursue a relationship with Philadelphia
radio personality Elaine Soncini.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 58, has maintained his innocence. No date has been
set for his trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, 54, of Collingswood, has said the rabbi promised to pay
him $30,000 to kill his wife. Jenoff and his alleged accomplice,
Paul Daniels, 27, of Pennsauken, have both pleaded guilty to
aggravated manslaughter and have agreed to testify against
Neulander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
