</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- German politicians are stepping up calls for a ban on a
right-wing political party, one of the steps being considered in Germany's
attempts to stem an outbreak of neo-Nazi violence. Intelligence agencies have
enough information on the extreme-right National Democratic Party of Germany, or
NPD, for the country's highest court to enact a ban, Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's intelligence coordinator, Ernst Uhrlau, said. Chief government
spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye said the government would support a ban if it is
recommended by a group of federal and state officials considering proposals
concerning the NPD.
</P>
