<HEADLINE> President and first lady to take Adirondack vacation  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - The Clintons will celebrate the president's
54th birthday with a three-day getaway in the Adirondack Mountains,
Hillary Clinton said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have a nice long weekend. I'm really looking
forward to it,'' the first lady said in an interview with The
Associated Press in Los Angeles, where she is attending the
Democratic Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she, the president and daughter Chelsea will spend
Friday, Saturday and Sunday at a private home near Lake Placid. It
was unclear Saturday whose home would host the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't seen the property but it's described to me as very
beautiful - lots of woods and water,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the White House has booked 100 rooms at the Lake Placid
Holiday Inn for a presidential entourage.
</P>
<P>
   The president turns 54 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and U.S. Senate candidate got into some hot water
with residents of New York's Adirondacks last year when an
unidentified adviser told the New York Daily News the Clintons
would never vacation in the ''fly infested'' Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made a campaign swing through the picturesque
region in October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons have made Martha's Vineyard their steady summer
getaway spot and spent a few days there earlier this month. The
first lady used the break to hold fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   But since Mrs. Clinton waded into the Senate race in New York,
they have also been fitting in some time to unwind upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Clintons spent several days in Skaneateles in the
Finger Lakes region and went to the New York State Fair in
Syracuse. Aides say they may return again this year to visit the
State Fair that runs Aug. 24 to Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate New York is heavily Republican but the first lady has
spent a significant amount of time there courting support. Still,
recent polls show her trailing opponent U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio
upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the first lady planned a low-key trip and was not
expected to campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
