<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loretta Young Remembered  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In 90 feature movies from 1927 to 1953,
Loretta Young portrayed the essence of femininity, splendidly
coifed, handsomely dressed, her high-cheeked beauty augmented by
makeup artists, ready to be swept off her feet by Cary Grant, Clark
Gable, Tyrone Power and other leading men.
</P>
<P>
   Her essence carried over into television. Every week she began
''The Loretta Young Show'' by entering a room in the most elegant
of gowns and sweeping toward the camera to introduce a new episode.
</P>
<P>
   Glamour photographer John Engstead once observed another side of
Loretta Young. He recalled entering her Paramount dressing room one
evening during the mid 1930s:
</P>
<P>
   ''Her makeup was off, there were shadows under her eyes, and she
looked tired. I could not believe her telephone conversation. She
was reading the riot act to some studio executive. She told him in
no uncertain terms what she would and would not do, made herself
crystal clear and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was amazed by this transformation from the sweet, shy
Gretchen (her real name) to this strong businesswoman.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a side Loretta Young rarely revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her contemporary, Joan Crawford, whose fierce
self-promotion was legendary, Young maintained an aura of
sweetness. She even exacted fines from any film worker who swore on
her sets.
</P>
<P>
   But no star could have maintained a 35-year career without an
iron will. She chose her projects with great care, and her
contracts assured that she would receive star treatment.
</P>
<P>
   She avoided confrontations with directors and co-stars, always
imposing her will with a velvet touch.
</P>
<P>
   With ''The Loretta Young Show,'' she was able to maintain almost
complete control; her then-husband, Thomas Lewis, was the producer.
She took part in the casting and the selection of stories. She
insisted that every episode of the anthology series (she appeared
in half of them) should contain an uplifting message.
</P>
<P>
   When the series went into syndication, she decreed that her
glamorous entrances be eliminated. She worried that over time her
gowns would appear dated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 she launched ''The New Loretta Young Show.'' It lasted
six months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't like the things the producers offered, and they
didn't like the things that I offered,'' she explained afterward.
''So we reached an impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's all right,'' she had said. ''I don't feel any
compulsion to be acting again. I've been doing it since I was 12
years old, and that's enough for anyone. I must say I don't miss
getting up at 4 in the morning to be on the set and ready to shoot
at 9. Don't miss it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   After her television career ended, she became a businesswoman,
joining the Schick company with a division that marketed a
beauty-foam maker. She once told of her negotiations with a Schick
executive: ''I warned him that I wasn't the easiest person in the
world to work with. I don't say yes to everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Young returned to acting for the 1986 television movie
''Christmas Eve'' and the 1989 television movie ''Lady in a
Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   In later years she continued her longtime devotion to Catholic
charities and lived in Palm Springs with her third husband, dress
designer Jean Louis. He died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Young died Saturday of ovarian cancer at 87.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 1927 </TRAILER>
