<HEADLINE> Combat exercise brings thousands of soldiers back to Rome  </HEADLINE>
With AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. (AP) - It looks like old times at the former Griffiss
Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Army National Guard military exercise is bringing
thousands of troops from across New York and 11 other states for
Exercise Empire Peak, simulating the activation and deployment of
National Guard forces into combat.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the annual training for New York's highest priority
command - the 27th Separate Infantry Brigade (Enhanced).
</P>
<P>
   The exercise is meant to prepare troops for an exercise next
year at the Army's Joint Readiness Training Center at Fort Polk,
La., Lt. Col. Paul Fanning said Friday. Griffiss was chosen because
it mirrored facilities and conditions at Fort Polk.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, soldiers will board Blackhawk helicopters at
Griffiss and take off for a night air assault into one of Fort
Drum's training areas. The assault will secure a dirt airstrip for
C-130 aircraft to bring more troops and equipment from Griffiss
through the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, military convoys will leave Griffiss and
travel from Rome to Boonville. From there, they'll turn north to
Fort Drum.
</P>
<P>
   Troops will be carrying arms and will assume defensive positions
as though traveling to a hostile site, Fanning said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Realism and authenticity is the bottom line of the exercise,''
he said. ''This is not easy. It's very sophisticated and
challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the largest military gathering at the former base
since it closed five years ago. The site is now known as Griffiss
Business and Technology Park.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've been coming in since last Sunday, usually in the
morning,'' Dunkin Donuts manager Kristi Serra said of the soldiers.
''It's nice to have them back even if it is temporary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
