<DOCNO> APW20000812.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Frerotte Concedes QB Job  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- Although Denver Broncos coach Mike
Shanahan insists the starting quarterback job is still open, Gus
Frerotte thinks otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks into training camp, Frerotte said that barring
injury, Brian Griese will be the starter this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've gone through camp now and he's going to be the
starter,'' Frerotte said Friday as the Broncos prepared for
Sunday's preseason game against the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, that's just the way it is,'' Frerotte said. ''He's been
in this system, he's been with the coaches, he's been with the
players. This is how it had to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte doesn't harbor any ill feelings towards Griese, who
replaced John Elway as the Broncos' starter last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brian played well,'' Frerotte said. ''You have to hand it to
him. He came out every day and he worked hard. Neither one of us
missed a throw at all. We threw 300, 400 balls a day and we pushed
each other. I don't have any animosity toward him or anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   More than three weeks before the Sept. 4 season opener at St.
Louis, Shanahan declined to announce his starter.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone thinks he'll be second team, that's up to him,''
Shanahan said. ''But what I try to do is sit back and look at every
practice and look at every game and see how people perform and then
make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte, 29, finds himself in a similar role to the one he had
in Detroit last season when he backed up Charlie Batch, who was
drafted ahead of Griese in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte, who signed a 1-year deal with the Broncos in March,
said he does not regret his decision to sign with Denver rather
than return to Detroit, where Batch is recovering from a broken
right leg.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd prefer the chance to become a starter. I don't see myself
as a backup. That's just my nature,'' he said. ''If it happens all
year where Brian starts every game, so be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 1957 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Quann Predicts Gold Future  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Megan Quann snuggles up each night with a
stopwatch in her hand. As she drifts off, the 16-year-old swimmer's
head is filled with goal times for the 100-meter breaststroke and
thoughts of beating Olympic champion Penny Heyns in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's going down,'' Quann predicted. ''I'm going to be there,
race my heart out and win that gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Brash words indeed, but Quann possesses the speed, confidence
and fearlessness that seemingly belong to every young swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   She set an American record of 1 minute, 7.12 seconds in the 100
breast preliminaries Thursday in the U.S. Olympic trials. She then
fell short of her world record prediction in Friday's final, but
still won in 1:07.26.
</P>
<P>
   She'll try to make the team in the 200 breast beginning with
Sunday's prelims.
</P>
<P>
   ''I plan on taking that one, too,'' she said. ''I like being the
number one seed and having some tough competition.''
</P>
<P>
   A rivalry with her brother, who's two years older, helped
develop Quann's confidence. As a 6-year-old, she couldn't complete
one lap of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''I absolutely hated it,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, her father enrolled his kids in lessons to
keep them from spending the summer watching television. Quann
struggled again, needing to stop six times during a lap of
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Told to try breaststroke, Quann didn't know how and became
embarrassed in front of the other kids. The instructors placed her
in a group of 5- and 6-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ''That motivated me to do much better,'' she said. ''I went to
my first swim meet and won every event I raced. It all started off
with me against my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   She's never lost that competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   On the closet door of Quann's bedroom in Puyallup, Wash., is
posted the world breaststroke rankings. Each time she beats one of
the times she crosses it off.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is 1:05.49. Heyns' world record is 1:06.52
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll go that 1:05,'' she said. ''I visualize my races every
night before I go to bed. I visualize everything going perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Most amazing about Quann's American record in the trials is that
it came without her tapering, a process in which swimmers gradually
decrease their yardage and weight training leading up to a major
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, Quann was swimming 15,000 meters daily -- about
nine miles. She cut back to 7,000 meters last Monday -- still a
large amount.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nothing compared to the 50,000 meters she once swam
over a 24-hour period with her club team.
</P>
<P>
   Quann does all this despite the nearest pool being 45 minutes
from her house. Her day begins at 4:30 a.m. She swims from 6-8
a.m., goes to school for 4&AMP;frac12; hours, hits the gym for an hour, then
swims from 6-8 p.m. In between, she spends 2-3 hours commuting
daily.
</P>
<P>
   And yeah, she finds time for fun at the movies, the mall and
hiking near Mount Rainier with her friends and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm having a blast,'' she said. ''This is the time of my life.
I just made the Olympics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
