<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Swim Trials Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Gold medalist Tom Dolan doesn't like the
idea of sharing the pool with 1,300 other swimmers at the U.S.
Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, who will get a chance to defend his title in the
400-meter individual medley in the Sydney Games after making the
American team Thursday, is one of the strongest critics of the
decision to expand the trials.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, there were 570 competitors in the trials. This
year, there were 1,309 entrants at the Indiana University
Natatorium for the eight-day meet. That makes for a crowded pool
during warm-up and practice sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like World War III out there,'' Dolan said. ''You're
throwing elbows at 14-year-old kids. It's ridiculous. I lay awake
at night wondering who makes these decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Swimming lowered the qualifying standards for the trials,
hoping to give younger swimmers a chance to gain valuable
experience and also compensate for not having a national
championship in this Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan scoffs at the logic, saying ''we're supposed to be here
picking an Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the decision to have the trials in August, a
mere month away from the lighting of the flame in Sydney. According
to Dolan, the sport could have generated more media coverage if the
Olympic team had been picked a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a terrible decision, as bad a decision has USA
Swimming has made,'' he said. ''That sums up the small thinkers in
the sport compared with the big thinkers. Some people say we would
get too much publicity and put the swimmers under too much pressure
by having the trials earlier. I thought that was the point -- to
make the sport bigger and more popular.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DON'T COUNT HER OUT: Angie Wester-Krieg is already the oldest
woman in the U.S. Olympic swim trials -- and she's still not
thinking about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old swimmer from Campbell, Calif., doesn't even rule
out coming back in four years for another trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be jumping the gun to say I'm going to do it or I'm
not going to do it,'' said Wester-Krieg, competing in her record
sixth trials.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, she finished 25th in the 200-meter butterfly,
failing to advance to the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just like being an athlete,'' Wester-Krieg said. ''I thank
God that he provided me with the ability to do that at this level
for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Peter Krieg, is also her coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me, joking around, that if we come to another trials,
he wants to have a 2-year-old right here,'' Wester-Krieg said,
patting her hip. ''He's so understanding about my lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   She also works 20 hours a week as a tax consultant in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't say I'm not tired when the alarm clock goes off in the
morning,'' Wester-Krieg said. ''But training is what I enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TOWERING SHEALY: At 6-foot-3, Courtney Shealy towers over most
women. Those extra inches might have helped her make the Olympics
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Shealy provided one of the biggest surprises in the early days
of the trials when she finished second in the 100-meter backstroke,
earning a spot on the team that will be heading to Sydney. She beat
out American record holder Lea Maurer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess my 6-3 helps my reach,'' Shealy said. ''I've never
been ashamed of my height. It definitely helped me here.''
</P>
<P>
   Shealy, of Columbia, S.C., was part of University of Georgia
teams that won back-to-back national championships. She also played
volleyball for the Lady Bulldogs, becoming the first Division I
female athlete to compete in two sports on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Shealy didn't expect to make the team in the 100 backstroke,
figuring her best chance would come in the 100 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Total shock,'' she said, ''but a very excellent surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER AND COACH: Renee Riggs stands out at the Indiana
University Natatorium, coaching swimmers while lugging a
5-month-old baby on her chest.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs and her husband, Victor, are coaching 17-year-old Kaitlin
Sandeno, who already has made her first Olympic team. The couple
also is getting used to life with their first child, Abigail.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's very good-natured,'' Renee Riggs said while the infant
gnawed on an entry sheet in her mother's hands. ''We're very lucky.
She's easily entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggs takes special precautions when strolling around the
crowded, slippery deck.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to be really careful,'' she said. ''When I'm walking
around, I hold her arms in so they don't get whacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she may be carrying around a future Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's already been swimming,'' Riggs said. ''She splashes her
hands and gets her face wet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 2001 </TRAILER>
