<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torrential rain causes heavy damage to Stratford  </HEADLINE>
dcfonstv
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATFORD, Conn. (AP) - Several motorists had to be rescued from
their vehicles and numerous properties were damaged after a storm
dumped nearly 8 inches of rain in Fairfield county early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   No fatalities or serious injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   A Stratford town police cruiser and three ambulances were
heavily damaged after being inundated with flood water, Town
Manager Mark Barnhart said. One of the ambulances stalled in high
water while carrying patients, who were transferred to another
ambulance and brought to the hospital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said several businesses in the town center were forced
to close Saturday because of flood damage. Officials said numerous
homeowners were cleaning out water from their basements.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Natalie's Antiques on Main Street said they were
not sure if insurance would cover the tens of thousands of dollars
in damage done by the several feet of water inside their shop.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is all I've worked for,'' owner Natalie Fisher said.
''This is my retirement money.''
</P>
<P>
   State Transportation Department crews were called in to help
clear roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would appear that we took the brunt of the storm,''
Barnhart said. ''It was a freakish storm event. The force of the
water was quite awesome. I can't describe it. You have it picking
up large objects. An ambulance was swept sideways by the current.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said the town is investigating whether a
recently-installed pump system, designed to prevent flooding, did
its job.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said several businesses do not have flood insurance. He
said town officials may seek state or federal aid to clean up the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport authorities also reported rescuing motorists stranded
in their vehicles. No serious injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Low-lying parts of Stratford are prone to flooding, partly
because of viaducts near the Metro North rail line, Barnhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
