<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Coach Fassel Still Upbeat  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite being winless in the preseason and
giving away a game to Jacksonville with a last-second blunder, Jim
Fassel isn't overly concerned about the New York Giants three weeks
before the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   The positives far outweigh the negatives, almost to the point
that rookie linebacker Jack Golden's now infamous tackling of a
teammate to set up Jacksonville's game-winning touchdown on Friday
night seems insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   A little less than 24 hours after the 16-13 loss to the Jaguars,
Fassel said Saturday night that the play of his starting offense
and defense has been very good so far.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kerry Collins continued to look good, completing 10
of 19 passes for 110 yards. Receiver Amani Toomer came up with a
big touchdown catch and the defense limited Jacksonville's offense
to three field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''All in all, we made a lot of improvement in a lot of areas,''
Fassel said. ''That's the way I approached the team afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of screaming about the loss on Friday night, Fassel
didn't get down on his team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went down there with an attitude to win,'' Fassel said.
''It was important for us to win that ballgame. We fought hard, but
when you lose a game like that, it can rip your heart out in a
preseason game. It can turn you in the wrong direction mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were a lot of long faces in the locker room, Fassel
told them that all the mistakes they made were correctable,
including the two on the game-winning touchdown that started when
Fred Lewis intercepted a Jonathan Lewis' pass around the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of falling down in the end zone, Lewis started to come
out and Golden tackled him, causing a fumble that Jaguars tight end
Brandon Christenson recovered for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got a list of 11 things that, in my opinion, led directly
to us losing that game,'' Fassel said. ''I would say four, five or
six of them, if we eliminate just those, we win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis should have fallen to the ground immediately after the
interception, Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   The tackle was inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what you learned in high school, which is crazy, don't
ever tackle the guy, don't ever tackle the guy,'' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel didn't go through all 11 mistakes, but he said the Giants
twice ran out of the bounds when they could have kept the clock
running in the closing minutes. He added on the game-winning drive,
the defense blew a pass coverage on fourth-and-17.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did everything we could to win that game and then we did
everything wrong to give it back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Fassel was reminded that most of the mistakes were made by
second and third team players who won't be playing when the Giants
open against Arizona on Sept. 3, he said the mistakes still need to
be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of those rookie might be playing for us,'' Fassel said.
''They have to grow up pretty quick because they (the games) are
going to be counting pretty quick. That's our job to hammer at them
so we get it straightened out by the time we play Arizona.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 2048 </TRAILER>
