<HEADLINE> Services remember slain girl  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. (AP) - Friends and family gathered to bury a
slain teen-ager, hoping to ''find comfort'' amid the pain and
anguish of the girl's death and the arrest of her 16-year-old
friend.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Amber J. Brockway, a 15-year-old honor student who
would have entered her junior year, was found Monday morning in an
abandoned building near Seneca Lake. Her schoolmate and friend,
Joshua J. Horein, remained in the Schuyler County Jail, accused of
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Brockway was killed by several blows to the head.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Beverly Karr-Lyon, pastor at the First Presbyterian
Church, led hundreds of mourners in an emotional service Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We come together today to find comfort in the midst of so many
unanswered questions and such a painful loss,'' Karr-Lyon said in
her eulogy. ''A large part of life is the struggle against every
person's own smallness and fear and anger. May we look inward and
pray for forgiveness of thoughts of anger we have had, and let go
of our fears and our rage in order to minimize the chance that
something like this will happen again.'' The eulogy followed an
emotional song called ''Now You're Gone,'' performed by Michael
Fredo, a local pop singer whom Amber admired.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Amber's cousins told the gathering how she always had
time to listen and give comfort, had a cheerful spirit, a ready
smile and a concern for friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
