<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut Post reporter dead at 56  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - James G. Clark, a Connecticut Post
reporter and columnist who covered everything from food to politics
during his more than 30-year career, died Friday at St. Vincent's
Medical Center. He was 56.
</P>
<P>
   Clark had suffered from cirrhosis of the liver and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jim was a very talented writer who knew Bridgeport inside and
out. His presence in this city, along with his writings, will be
missed,'' said Robert H. Laska, president and CEO of the Thomson
Newspapers' Southern Connecticut Strategic Marketing Group, which
publishes the Post.
</P>
<P>
   Clark started his career in 1963 in Stamford with The Advocate.
He began work for the Bridgeport Telegram in 1969, reporting on
Bridgeport City Hall and the General Assembly in Hartford. He also
wrote Dining Out, a restaurant review column; the Produce Basket
column, which featured tips about buying and preparing fruits and
vegetables; and various features.
</P>
<P>
   The Telegram merged with the Bridgeport Post in 1992 to become
the Connecticut Post.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was a former Connecticut Society of Professional
Journalists president, treasurer, secretary and longtime member of
its board of directors. A scholarship in his memory is being
established by the Connecticut SPJ Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was born in Monongahela, Pa., and lived in Stamford for 25
years before moving to Bridgeport in 1977. A graduate of Stamford
High School, he received a bachelor of arts degree from the
University of Connecticut in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his mother, Virginia M. Clark, of Delray
Beach, Fla.; two brothers, Lewis W. Clark, of Norwalk, and Robert
R. Clark, of Marlborough, Mass.; a sister, Carol V. Clark, of
Houston, Texas; and several nieces and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held Tuesday at 2 p.m. at Golden Hill
United Methodist Church.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
