<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates 9, Diamondbacks 6  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Kevin Young's infield single turned into two
runs as third baseman Matt Williams threw wildly in the seventh
inning, ending Pittsburgh's six-game losing streak against Curt
Schilling and rallying the Pirates past Arizona 9-6 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Aramis Ramirez hit a grand slam in the eighth off reliever
Johnny Ruffin and drove in five runs as the Pirates won for only
the third time in 11 games. Arizona has lost eight of 13.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling (9-7) had been 3-0 since the trade to Arizona and was
9-1 in his last 10 starts against the Pirates before allowing five
runs and eight hits in seven innings. His last previous loss to
Pittsburgh was on July 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell's two-run homer off reliever Rich Loiselle gave Arizona
a 4-3 lead, but Schilling -- who allowed only three earned runs in
26 innings in his first three Diamondbacks starts -- immediately
lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Aramis Ramirez doubled down the left field line and Alex Ramirez
singled a batter later, then stole second.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who entered in a double switch in the top of the seventh,
hit a hard grounder that Williams stopped by diving to his left.
Williams scrambled to his feet and appeared to have a play on Young
at first, but his throw sailed wide of the bag as both runners
scored. Young was credited with one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Young had been 1-for-21 in his career against Schilling, going
hitless in his previous 18 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sauerbeck (5-1) pitched 1 1-3 scoreless innings for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez and Matt Williams hit ninth-inning homers off Mike
Williams. Gonzalez homered for the second straight night, hitting
his 26th of the season; Matt Williams stopped an 0-for-12 slide
with just his fifth homer.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona quickly opened a 1-0 lead in the first as Tony Womack,
Bell and Gonzalez singled in succession against Todd Ritchie, who
came off the disabled list to make his first start since losing 4-1
to Schilling on July 23. That was Schilling's last start for the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller doubled in the second and scored on Schilling's
perfectly executed squeeze bunt to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   But Schilling couldn't hold that lead, either, as Jason Kendall
hit a two-run homer, his 10th, in a three-run fifth and Aramis
Ramirez followed Brian Giles' triple with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie lasted five innings, giving up two runs and seven hits.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Two of Ramirez's six homers this season are grand slams. He
also hit one July 28 against San Diego. ... The Pirates' two homers
stopped a streak of five games without a homer. ... Womack stole
second in each of the first two innings, giving him 13 stolen bases
in 10 games. ... Gonzalez has six of Arizona's last 11 homers. ...
Pirates pinch-hitters are 5-for-33 since July 1 and have two RBIs
in 53 games -- Aramis Ramirez's two-run double June 30 at
Philadelphia. ... Arizona lost for only the second time in nine
games at Three Rivers Stadium. ... The Diamondbacks had been 6-1
overall against the Pirates this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 2211 </TRAILER>
