<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Puzzled By Texas' Glynn  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Texas Rangers pitcher Ryan Glynn was
released from the hospital Saturday night, with doctors still
unclear as to why the rookie fainted in the dugout a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn underwent a battery of tests Friday night and Saturday to
determine why he lost consciousness a few minutes after he had been
removed from a game against Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn was examined by three doctors on Saturday -- Rangers
internist Dr. John Martin, a cardiologist and a neurologist. None
of the doctors was able to pinpoint the cause of Glynn's physical
problems and he hasn't been cleared to resume baseball activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers said Glynn was resting at home Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended for 10 minutes during Friday night's game
while medical personnel attended to Glynn.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn had been taken out of the game with two out in the fifth
after the Red Sox scored four runs in the inning to stretch their
lead to 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Gametime temperature was 98 degrees and Glynn had thrown 95
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the fifth, Rangers manager Johnny Oates called
for a paramedics cart to come to the dugout, where Glynn was lying
on ground.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn was down for about five minutes, but was fully conscious
and alert when he was taken by ambulance to Arlington Memorial
Hospital at about 9:15 p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, who gave up eight runs and seven hits over 4 2-3 innings
in a 7-3 loss to Boston, is scheduled to start on Tuesday night
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he won't be sure about his rotation until he knows
more about Glynn's availability.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not necessarily undecided,'' said Oates of Tuesday
night's starter. ''It's unknown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 2220 </TRAILER>
