<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Aug. 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iraq Criticizes S. Arabia, Kuwait
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- An allied airstrike hit a warehouse storing
humanitarian aid, killing two people, Iraqi officials said, prompting Baghdad to
accuse Saudi Arabia and Kuwait on Saturday of backing aggression. In Friday's
strike, U.S. and British planes struck in the city of Samawa, 168 miles south of
Baghdad, hitting the main food ration distribution center used to store food
allowed under the U.N. oil-for-food deal, Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh
told reporters. Along with two civilians killed, 19 others were injured, Iraqi
officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Buchanan Claims Reform Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Pat Buchanan claimed the Reform Party nomination
today but said his long-shot presidential bid may have no chance if rivals
succeed in keeping him from the party's $12.5 million in federal funding.
Supporters of party founder Ross Perot say the nomination is John Hagelin's and
the money should be his. In a move that could render the federal subsidy less
crucial for him, Hagelin chose as his running mate an Internet multimillionaire.
No one is likely to see the federal cash until the issue is thrashed out by the
Federal Election Commission and then, probably, the courts.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mau Mau Rebels Celebrate 50 Years
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NYERI, Kenya (AP) -- Aging rebels in shabby suits gathered in this central
Kenyan city Saturday to mark the 50th anniversary of their fight against British
colonial rule, sing old revolutionary songs and ask the government to finally
legalize their movement. The 250 men were veterans of the Mau Mau movement,
which was banned on Aug. 12, 1950, by British authorities, who considered it a
secret society that was a danger to the Kenya colony. Despite Kenya's
independence in 1963, the movement remains illegal and the men ignored by
successive Kenyan governments.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Complete Western Tour
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRESCOTT, Ariz. (AP) -- George W. Bush vowed to ''restore the military power
of the United States'' today as he and former rival John McCain completed a
three-day Western campaign tour. Both Bush and Sen. McCain, R-Ariz., sounded
military themes, here in McCain's home state and earlier at a rally near a naval
complex in Everett, Wash. They were Bush's final campaign events before he steps
out of the spotlight for the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mayor Needs Black Vote in Selma
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. (AP) -- Joe Smitherman admits he was opposed to blacks voting
''in mass'' when he was first elected mayor 36 years ago. In fact, he was a
professed segregationist in the early years, but Selma kept re-electing him.
Now, Smitherman is counting on black voters -- 65 percent of the city's
electorate -- to win his 10th consecutive term in office. Three black candidates
are also on the Aug. 22 ballot, and Smitherman's staunchest opponents have
revved up a kick-him-out campaign with signs planted across the city of 22,600
that read: ''Joe's Gotta Go.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwan President Stopping in L.A.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- An influential Asian leader is traveling to Los
Angeles on Sunday. He has promised he won't talk to reporters, hold public
events or meet with top U.S. officials. Chen Shui-bian's 16-hour layover will be
low key not because he's from a rogue state shunned by Washington. It's because
he's the president of Taiwan. Although Taiwan is a longtime friend of the United
States, a global trading power and a vibrant democracy, the island's leaders are
treated like pariahs on the rare occasions they are allowed to visit America.
The reason is China.	   China considers Taiwan a breakaway province that should
reunify with the mainland. The communist government in Beijing protests loudly
when other countries treat Taiwan as if it is an independent nation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic's Moves Worry U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is worried that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic may be preparing stir up new problems in the
Balkans with a move against Montenegro. Only 14 months ago, NATO airstrikes
drove Serb forces out of Kosovo to end Milosevic's crackdown on ethnic Albanians
in the Serbian province. Montenegro, Serbia's junior partner in the Yugoslav
federation, is seen as a potential target because it has a pro-Western
government whose leaders have made no secret of a desire for independence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Padres Beat Marlins 2-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Eric Owens blooped a single with two outs in the 10th inning to
break a scoreless tie and send the San Diego Padres past the Florida Marlins 2-1
tonight. Desi Relaford singled off Antonio Alfonseca with one out in the 10th
and moved to second on pinch-hitter John Mabry's hard-hit ground ball to second,
which Luis Castillo initially bobbled before making the play.
</P>
