<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman, Family Break For Sabbath  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they do every Saturday, Joseph Lieberman and his family began
their day with a quiet walk to temple. But on this Sabbath day,
about 20 Secret Service agents walked behind them and two vans
filled with agents trailed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, returned to his synagogue for the
first time since he was picked to be Al Gore's running mate. He is
the first Jew ever chosen for a national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The senator from Connecticut entered Kesher Israel sanctuary in
Washington, D.C., wearing a prayer shawl over his shoulders and his
yarmulke, the traditional Jewish skullcap worn to cover the head in
reverence to God. He and his wife, Hadassah, sat separately, as all
men and women must do.
</P>
<P>
   The Torah portion read for this week's service included the Ten
Commandments; Rabbi Barry Freundel also spoke of ''Joe'' and his
''historic'' run for the vice presidency. He warned fellow
worshippers not to act ''triumphalistic,'' or feel that ''just
because he is one of ours ... that makes him better than anybody
else.'' Freundel advised the congregation -- a standing-room only
crowd in a synagogue that seats 320 -- to remain humble throughout
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a test case,'' Freundel said during a half-hour
sermon. ''We could squander this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Freundel said Lieberman's run would be an opportunity for others
to learn about Orthodox Jews and see what Jewish people have to
contribute to society. He noted that the reaction of the American
public had generally been positive, aside from some hate group
discussions on the Internet and comments from an NAACP leader in
Dallas who was later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Like other observant Jews -- Orthodox, Conservative or Reform --
the Liebermans began the Sabbath at sundown Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They had been out on the campaign trail. But while Gore
conducted press interviews, Lieberman's motorcade slipped away
without fanfare. The family boarded a train to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabbath is the traditional Jewish day of rest, a time to
pray and reflect on God's creations. It stems from the Torah, the
word of God, which says: ''For in six days, God made heaven, earth
and sea, and all that is in them, and He rested on the seventh day.
Therefore, God blessed the Sabbath day and made it holy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has said he will not campaign on the Sabbath. The
senator believes he may still work during that time, but only to
promote ''the respect and protection of human life and
well-being.'' Jewish law, in fact, requires violation of the
Sabbath if doing so will save someone's life, his Rabbi Freundel
has said.
</P>
<P>
   Observant Jews like the Liebermans also keep kosher. It is
forbidden to eat certain animals like pig or shellfish. Meat cannot
be eaten with dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, while traveling with Gore aboard Air Force Two,
Lieberman has been served kosher meals. On the Wednesday flight out
of Nashville, for example, while most of those aboard the plane
were served barbecued pork ribs, Lieberman and his family were
offered vegetable lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press Writer Janelle Carter in
Washington contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-12-00 2304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000812.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mets 3, Giants 2  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Benny Agbayani's gaffe cost the New York Mets
just a run, not the game.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani allowed a run to score when he handed the ball to a
7-year-old fan in the stands when there were only two outs, but the
Mets rallied to beat the San Francisco Giants 3-2 on Todd Zeile's
two-run double in the seventh inning Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Down 1-0 in the fourth, the Giants loaded the bases with one out
and Bobby Estalella hit a lazy fly to left field. Agbayani ran
toward the line to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   With Jeff Kent tagging from third and scoring, Agbayani jogged
toward the seats and handed the ball to Jake Burns, who broke into
a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was weird,'' the young fan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was eating a hot dog and then all of a sudden he had a ball
in his other hand,'' said his father, Jim.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Agbayani gave the ball away, another fan appeared to
shout that there were only two outs, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Burns said he did not know how many outs there were when
the kooky play occurred, but his father did.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured I was wrong. Then I saw his expression,'' he said,
referring to his son, ''and I couldn't care less.''
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani grabbed the ball back from the fan and threw it to the
infield, but the runners were given two extra bases on the error.
Ellis Burks, who reached on shortstop Mike Bordick's throwing
error, scored a second run on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Walker, then with Montreal, made a similar slipup on April
24, 1994, when he handed a ball to a 9-year-old boy in the front
row at Dodger Stadium after catching a foul fly with one out and a
runner on first.
</P>
<P>
   After Agbayani warmed up in the top of the fifth, he directed
that the ball be given to the boy.
</P>
<P>
   That was the play of the game until the Mets rallied in the
seventh to win for the 15th time in 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Bubba Trammell led off with a walk -- the seventh
allowed by Giants starter Shawn Estes. Felix Rodriguez (4-2) came
in and got Bordick to pop out on a bunt attempt and struck out
Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   After Edgardo Alfonzo walked, Zeile lined a two-run double down
the right-field line to give the Mets the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton (12-7) was sharp for the Mets, allowing only two
unearned runs and five hits in seven innings to improve to 9-0
against San Francisco. He held the Giants hitless in 10 at-bats
with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez pitched the ninth for his 29th save in 33
chances. He struck out Barry Bonds looking with a runner on first
to end it.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have lost two straight following a four-game winning
streak and remained two games ahead of Arizona in the NL West. The
Mets are still 2&AMP;frac12; games behind Atlanta in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd game that was delayed 38 minutes by rain after the
second inning, the Mets were unable to score in the fifth when
Estes walked four of the first five batters in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton walked on four pitches to open the inning, but was
erased on Bordick's double-play grounder. Estes then threw 11
straight balls, walking Bell and Alfonzo and falling behind 3-0 to
Zeile, before walking him on a 3-1 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Agbayani, who must have wished he had gotten the
day off. Agbayani, who went 0-for-4 with two strikeouts, grounded
out to short to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Bordick hit a solo homer in the third to give the Mets a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Estes induced two double-play grounders, giving him a major
league-leading 30 this season. ... Alfonzo, who had eight multihit
games in his last nine contests, went 0-for-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
