<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barricaded man shoots three officers during Brooklyn incident  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A gunman engaged in a standoff at his Brooklyn
home shot and wounded three city police officers before being
fatally shot by police Saturday night, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The almost seven-hour standoff with the gunman, identified as
Albert Alalouf, started Saturday afternoon after his parents had
earlier gone to the 61st Precinct in Brooklyn to report that
Alalouf had purchased several weapons on Friday, and then told them
he intended to ''shoot and kill police officers,'' Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   New York City cop Gregory John was among the first officers to
respond to Alalouf's residence in the Gravesend section of
Brooklyn, where the man opened fire with his shotgun. The officers
returned fire, forcing Alalouf back inside the home at 16 Parkway
Court, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   John, 32, an Emergency Service Unit officer with 10 years on the
job, was rushed to Kings County Hospital in serious condition after
he was shot in the shoulder around 1:30 p.m., said Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, Alalouf remained barricaded inside the home
as police circled the Brooklyn residence. But around 8 p.m.,
officers searching the perimeter of the home came across Alalouf,
who opened fire, police said.
</P>
<P>
   One officer was hit in the face and the other in the leg. They
were taken to Kings County Hospital, but their injuries were not
life-threatening, said Detective Joseph Pentangelo. Police did not
immediately identify the officers, but both were members of the
Emergency Service Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Officers fired back at Alalouf, and killed him. He was
pronounced dead at the scene, Pentangelo said. It was not clear
whether the two wounded officers fired back at Alalouf or if the
shots came from other officers on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Three other officers were being treated for injuries that were
not gunshot-related.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities credited John's bulletproof vest with saving his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani displayed the officer's Kevlar vest, which contained at
least eight holes where the buckshot had torn into it.
</P>
<P>
   John was actually wearing two vests - his personal vest beneath
his uniform, and a heavier ESU vest worn over his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God for the vest,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-12-00 2337 </TRAILER>
