<DOCNO> APW20000812.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan President Stopping in L.A.  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- An influential Asian leader is traveling
to Los Angeles on Sunday. He has promised he won't talk to
reporters, hold public events or meet with top U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   His 16-hour layover will be low key not because he's from a
rogue state shunned by Washington. It's because he's the president
of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Although Taiwan is a longtime friend of the United States, a
global trading power and a vibrant democracy, the island's leaders
are treated like pariahs on the rare occasions they are allowed to
visit America. The reason is China.
</P>
<P>
   China considers Taiwan a breakaway province that should reunify
with the mainland. The communist government in Beijing protests
loudly when other countries treat Taiwan as if it is an independent
nation.
</P>
<P>
   China began complaining almost as soon as Taiwan's new
president, Chen Shui-bian, announced he would make a brief stop in
Los Angeles while traveling to Latin America, where several nations
have formal diplomatic ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China's state-run Xinhua News Agency said the government felt
''strong resentment'' about the U.S. decision to give Chen a
transit visa. The report urged Washington ''to avoid severely
damaging bilateral relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing it safe, the U.S. State Department has discouraged
members of Congress from meeting with Chen during his layover.
</P>
<P>
   Chen on Saturday pulled out of a planned meeting with four
members of Congress from California, which was to be held in a
private home in Los Angeles Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I regret that the State Department and administration
officials have pressured President Chen to refrain from meeting
with Congress during his visit,'' Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., said
in a staff statement issued in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Taipei on Sunday morning, Taiwanese Foreign Ministry official
Wu Tzu-dan would not specifically comment on the canceled meeting.
But Wu told reporters that Chen's schedule was tight and he did not
have time for such meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Chen will spend most of his time in the hotel,''
said Wu, a vice minister. ''There's no time to do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Taiwanese and American editorial writers have said
Washington should ignore Beijing and invite Chen to the White
House. Rather than lecture China about its human rights record,
America should show Chinese leaders that places like Taiwan which
have ditched authoritarianism for democracy get rewarded with red
carpet treatment, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   But such a move could be dangerous, because China, the world's
No. 3 nuclear power, appears to be deadly serious about Taiwan,
which split from the mainland during civil war 51 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Washington allowed former Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui
to give a speech in 1995 at his alma mater, Cornell University, a
furious China responded by lobbing test missiles near Taiwan, which
is about 100 miles off the mainland's southeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   Any rise in tensions between China and Taiwan creates serious
worries for the United States, Taiwan's most likely defender in the
event of a war. The U.S. government is required by law to sell
weapons to Taiwan that it needs for defense, and Washington sent
warships near the island when China held another round of missile
tests in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's first U.S. trip as Taiwan's president will be a challenge
for the 49-year-old former Taipei mayor, lawyer and democracy
activist, said Stephen Yates, a senior policy analyst who follows
Taiwan for the Heritage Foundation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''How Chen handles this visit will leave a deep impression on
the Gore and Bush teams,'' Yates said, referring to the
presidential campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. ''If he does anything deemed too political or too
public, U.S. government attitudes could quickly turn against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his March election, Chen has tread lightly on the
potentially explosive China issue. He has assured Beijing he won't
declare independence as long as China doesn't attack, and he has
repeatedly invited Chinese leaders to meet with him to discuss
issues of their choice. Long-standing political disputes have
blocked a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Chen has also worked hard to cultivate a
strong relationship with the Clinton administration and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting this past week with Sen. Jack Reed, D-R.I.,
Chen told the lawmaker that he was grateful to President Clinton
for repeatedly reminding China that Taiwan is a democracy and any
resolution of the reunification issue should be agreeable to
Taiwanese voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the United States will continue to be a firm supporter
of the Republic of China,'' Chen said, referring to Taiwan by its
official name.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although I don't want America to be a mediator. I just hope it
can assume an even more positive balancing and stabilizing role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
